          type="button"
          class="series-details-close"
          data-series-details-close
          aria-label={t('library.series.details.close', language)}
        >×</button>
      </header>
      <div class="series-details-body">
        <section class="series-details-section">
          <p class="series-details-summary" data-series-details-summary></p>
          <p class="series-details-full" data-series-details-full></p>
        </section>
        <dl class="series-details-meta">
          <div class="series-details-meta-row">
            <dt>{t('library.series.details.assignedItems', language)}</dt>
            <dd data-series-details-assigned-count>0</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="series-details-meta-row" data-series-details-planned-row hidden>
            <dt>{t('library.series.details.plannedItems', language)}</dt>
            <dd data-series-details-planned-count></dd>
          </div>
          <div class="series-details-meta-row">
            <dt>{t('library.series.details.status', language)}</dt>
            <dd data-series-details-status-value></dd>
          </div>
          <div class="series-details-meta-row">
            <dt>{t('library.series.details.assetFolder', language)}</dt>
            <dd>
              <code data-series-details-asset-folder></code>
            </dd>
          </div>
          <div class="series-details-meta-row">
            <dt>{t('library.series.details.visibleInUniverse', language)}</dt>
            <dd data-series-details-visible></dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
        <section class="series-details-section">
          <h3 class="series-details-list-title">{t('library.series.details.assignedItems', language)}</h3>
          <ul class="series-details-list" data-series-details-list></ul>
        </section>
      </div>
    </aside>

    {/* ── Knowledge Atlas ──
          Alternative full-screen "all items" view, opened by the
          Knowledge Core widget's `data-library-view="all"` action. It is
          self-contained (own script for open/close/filter/search);
          selecting an item bridges back to the carousel through
          universe-layout's `[data-library-focus]` listener. Rendered at
          page level so it can cover the whole stage. */}
    <KnowledgeAtlas items={atlasItems} language={language} />

    {/* Orbit rotation controls — chevron pair pinned to the bottom of
        the viewport, OUTSIDE the orbit stage so they never overlap the
        focused card. The click handler in universe-layout.ts attaches
        a document-level delegate for [data-galaxy-rotate], so the
        buttons stay functional even though they live outside the stage. */}
    {showOrbitControls && (
      <div class="galaxy-orbit-controls" aria-hidden="false">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="galaxy-orbit-btn"
          data-galaxy-rotate
          data-direction="prev"
          aria-label={t('library.galaxy.rotatePrev', language)}
        ><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="14" height="14" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button>
        <button
          type="button"
          class="galaxy-orbit-btn"
          data-galaxy-rotate
          data-direction="next"
          aria-label={t('library.galaxy.rotateNext', language)}
        ><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="14" height="14" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button>
      </div>
    )}


  </div>
</LibraryLayout>

<style>
  /* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     /library — page shell + galaxy stage geometry
     Hard rules:
       - All colour/effect via --yuval-galaxy-*  (no hex anywhere)
       - All visible text via t()
       - RTL via inset-inline-* (logical properties)
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  /* ── Page-level lock: dark cosmic shell + no scroll ────────────────
     Two intentions in one rule:
       1. The body / html background-color is forced to match the
          cosmic floor `#00010d`, so iOS Safari rubber-band and
          URL-bar morph never expose a cream sliver above the dark
          header.
       2. `overflow: hidden` + `height: 100dvh` lock the page to the
          viewport in BOTH axes on every device. Per the user's
          request this screen never scrolls — the orbit dashboard
          (desktop) and the cleared hero+orbit-placeholder (mobile)
          are designed to fit inside a single viewport. Anything
          beyond is intentionally clipped rather than scrollable.
     Scoped via `:global()` + the page-root class so every other
     route keeps its native scroll. `:has()` is widely supported
     (Safari 15.4+, Chrome 105+, Firefox 121+); older engines fall
     back to normal page scroll. */
  :global(html:has(.library-dark-showcase)),
  :global(body:has(.library-dark-showcase)) {
    background-color: #00010d;
    height: 100dvh;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .library-root {
    position: relative;
    /* Hard viewport lock — the dashboard is sized to EXACTLY the area
       below the global header (`--library-dashboard-min-height` is
       defined by LibraryLayout as calc(100dvh - 72px)). Using `height`
       (not min-height) means library-root can never grow past the
       viewport, no matter how tall its inner content gets, so the page
       cannot scroll under any condition — even when the html/body
       `:has()` lock fails (older browsers, View Transition wrappers
       on iOS Safari). The calc() fallback covers the rare case where
       the layout var doesn't load. 100dvh inside the calc still tracks
       the dynamic viewport so the iOS URL-bar collapse doesn't leave a
       cosmic-bg strip uncovered. */
    height: var(--library-dashboard-min-height, calc(100dvh - 72px));
    width: 100%;
    /* Whole-screen unified backdrop. Mobile uses the two main layers;
       desktop adds side accents + vignette so the entire dashboard
       (sidebar + center + rail + recs) reads as one cosmic field.

       Background-color sampled directly from the dark outer pixels of
       galaxy-stage-core-medium.png (corners read RGB(0,1,13)). The
       earlier #0a0a1f estimate was ~3× brighter than reality and left
       a visible seam between the image edges and the page. With the
       sampled value, the image's outer dark pixels are continuous
       with the page bg. Scoped to .library-root via Astro style
       scoping — does not affect any other route. */
    background-color: #00010d;
    background-image:
      var(--yuval-galaxy-bg-radial-primary),
      var(--yuval-galaxy-bg-radial-secondary);
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text);
    /* Top padding kept tight (0.25rem) so the hero text sits close to
       the header line, per the user's preference. Side + bottom keep
       their original breathing room. Tablet + desktop overrides below
       follow the same rule — small top, generous sides/bottom. */
    padding: 0.25rem 1rem 4rem;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    isolation: isolate;
    /* `overflow: hidden` on BOTH axes — was `overflow-x: hidden` only,
       which let tall inner content (e.g. mobile flex column at the
       sticky-header offset) scroll vertically inside the root even
       when html/body had `overflow: hidden`. With the `height` cap
       above + this overflow lock, nothing can produce a scroll bar or
       a touch-scroll on any breakpoint. */
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  /* ── Cosmic scene background — full-page scene layer ────────────
     This is the global "knowledge universe" canvas. It is sized to
     `.library-root` and stacks behind every UI layer, which sit on
     top via `position: relative; z-index: 1` (see the
     `.library-root > :not(...)` rule below). */
  .knowledge-scene-background {
    /* `position: absolute`, NOT `fixed`. As a fixed layer this would
       re-base to the `<main transition:animate>` ancestor for the
       ~0.4s the page's View Transition runs on reload, then snap back
       to the viewport — a visible vertical jump (diagnosed live).
       Absolute keeps the containing block stable: it resolves to
       `.library-root`, the always-`position: relative` parent, which
       no view-transition machinery ever re-bases. `top` still reaches
       above .library-root's edge so the image tucks under the opaque
       header, which covers that strip. */
    position: absolute;
    top: calc(4rem - 130px);
    inset-inline: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
    overflow: hidden;
    z-index: 0;
  }
  .knowledge-scene-background img {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;          /* equivalent of background-size: cover   */
    object-position: center center; /* equivalent of background-position: center */
    /* Shift the scene 50px DOWN. Applied to the <img>, not the
       container, so the container box is unchanged: the 50px that
       overflows its bottom is clipped by the container's
       `overflow: hidden`, and the 50px gap opened at the top sits
       behind the opaque header. No container resize, no scrollbar. */
    transform: translateY(50px);
    user-select: none;
    -webkit-user-drag: none;
  }
  /* ── Theme-aware scene swap ──────────────────────────────────────
     The night galaxy is the default — dark mode renders the night
     PNG and hides the day photograph. Light mode (<html> without
     `.dark`) inverts both opacities so the day image fades in and
     the night image fades out. Both layers share the same absolute
     box so the swap is a pure cross-fade — no layout shift. */
  .knowledge-scene-img {
    transition: opacity var(--yuval-galaxy-motion-slow, 520ms)
                var(--yuval-galaxy-ease-soft, ease);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .knowledge-scene-img--night {
    opacity: 0;
  }
  .knowledge-scene-img--day {
    opacity: 0;
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .knowledge-scene-img--day {
    opacity: 1;
  }
  /* Day image — responsive fit strategy.
     ─ Mobile (<768px): inherits the shared `.knowledge-scene-background
       img` rule → object-fit: cover with the phone-cropped asset, which
       is already framed for portrait so cover loses nothing important.
     ─ Tablet + desktop (≥768px): override the shared rule's
       `width:100%; height:100%` so the image spans the full container
       width (= full viewport width) with its native ~16:9 aspect
       preserved via `height: auto`. The image is anchored to the top
       of `.knowledge-scene-background` (which itself sits 130px above
       library-root's top, so the top edge tucks behind the opaque
       header just like the night image does). On 16:9 displays the
       image fills both axes exactly. On taller viewports a band of
       the light-mode `.library-root` ivory gradient shows below the
       image as a soft sky-toned fallback. On ultra-wide viewports
       the container's `overflow: hidden` clips a small slice off the
       bottom — kept minimal by choosing top-anchor + aspect height
       rather than centring the image vertically.
     Specificity (0,2,2) outranks the generic `.knowledge-scene-
     background img` (0,1,1). Night mode is untouched — the selector
     only matches `--day`. */
  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .knowledge-scene-background img.knowledge-scene-img--day {
      width: 100%;
      height: auto;
      /* Bottom-anchored: image's bottom edge sticks to the bottom of
         the visible viewport so the workspace details near the floor
         are always on screen. On 16:9 displays the image fills end-to-
         end. On taller viewports (16:10, 4:3) a small light gradient
         band appears between the header and the image's top edge —
         intentional, reads as ambient sky. On ultra-wide viewports a
         slice of the image's TOP (ceiling area) is clipped, never the
         informative bottom half. */
      inset: auto 0 0 0;
      object-fit: unset;
      object-position: unset;
      transform: none;
    }
  }

  /* Soft radial vignette — keeps the central glow untouched and
     darkens only the edges so floating cards + side panels read
     cleanly against the bg without losing the cosmic atmosphere. */
  .knowledge-scene-overlay {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse at center,
      transparent 0%,
      transparent 35%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.45) 80%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.65) 100%);
  }
  /* Light-mode overlay — the dark vignette above would muddy the bright
     day scene, so in light mode it becomes a soft warm-ivory veil:
     fully clear through the center (the luminous core and the focused
     book card stay dominant) and lifting gently toward the edges so the
     floating cards never compete with the image's rings and labels.
     Kept subtle so the scene never washes out the cards or text. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .knowledge-scene-overlay {
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse at center,
      rgba(255, 253, 247, 0) 0%,
      rgba(255, 253, 247, 0) 46%,
      rgba(255, 253, 247, 0.20) 80%,
      rgba(255, 253, 247, 0.34) 100%);
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     LIGHT-MODE TUNING — page-level surfaces the galaxy tokens cannot
     reach: hardcoded dark page fills and a few light-on-dark text
     colors. All rules are gated on `html:not(.dark)`; dark mode never
     matches them, so the dark showcase stays byte-for-byte unchanged.
     (Coherent panel/header/glow theming is handled by the token block
     in galaxy.css scoped to `:root:not(.dark) .library-dark-showcase`.)
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

  /* Page base — minimal clean day-mode fallback. With the day scene
     image system removed, the page reads as a soft warm-blue gradient
     at the centre fading into a cool near-white field. The body/html
     bg uses the same near-white edge so iOS rubber-band, the URL-bar
     morph, and any layout sliver around the root all stay coherent. */
  :global(html:not(.dark):has(.library-dark-showcase)),
  :global(html:not(.dark) body:has(.library-dark-showcase)) {
    background-color: #eef5ff;
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .library-root {
    background:
      radial-gradient(circle at 50% 38%, rgba(210, 235, 255, 0.55), transparent 42%),
      linear-gradient(180deg, #ffffff 0%, #f7f9ff 48%, #eef5ff 100%);
    /* Light mode adds breathing room below the (now light-glass)
       header so the hero "ברוך הבא" eyebrow + "מרחב הידע" title never
       read as clipped or squeezed against the header line. Specificity
       (0,2,1) outranks the plain `.library-root` padding shorthand in
       the responsive @media blocks, so this wins at every breakpoint.
       Dark mode keeps the locked tight 0.25rem top padding. */
    padding-top: 1.1rem;
  }

  /* Starfield — navy dots on a bright sky read as dust, and the day
     asset already carries its own constellation of nodes. Fade the
     CSS starfield right back so it stays a whisper, never clutter. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .library-starfield {
    opacity: 0.10;
  }

  /* Center-card secondary link + metadata — authored in light-on-dark
     colors that vanish on the ivory scene. Repaint them in navy/slate
     so they stay readable directly beneath the focused book card. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .cc-secondary-link {
    color: #46556f;
    text-decoration-color: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.32);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .cc-secondary-link:hover,
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .cc-secondary-link:focus-visible {
    color: #16223c;
    text-decoration-color: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.70);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .cc-secondary-link:focus-visible {
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.40);
  }
  /* The chips now live INSIDE the dark image panel, so they read the
     same in both themes — no light-mode chip override needed. The
     standalone extras wrapper, section label and secondary link are
     all display:none in the new image-panel design, so their
     light-mode rules above are dead but kept for back-compat in case
     a future theme un-hides them.

     Reading-entry image-based CTA focus ring — the dark neon double
     glow is too loud on the bright day scene. Soften to a calm navy
     hairline that traces the image's actual rounded-rect shape. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .reading-entry-overlay:focus-visible .reading-entry-asset {
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 2px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.38),
      0 6px 18px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.20);
  }
  /* Card-selection confirmation halo — soften the cyan flash to a
     muted slate so the click feedback never sparks neon on daylight. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .library-root {
    --reading-entry-halo-color: rgba(70, 105, 150, 0.40);
  }

  /* Lightning overlay — SVG injected by `universe-core-effects.ts`.
     Each strike draws a multi-layer jagged bolt with branching forks
     from stage centre to the hovered card's centre.

     z-index: 25 — sits ABOVE orbit cards (z-index 3) so the bolt
     reaches the card's centre visibly, but BELOW the focused card
     (z-index 30) so a click-to-centered card never gets struck.

     mix-blend-mode: screen — the bolt is additive over whatever
     paints below it. White cores stay punchy on the dark cosmic
     scene, and accent-coloured glow tints (rather than overwrites)
     the card content it crosses. Stays non-interactive (clicks fall
     through to the cards underneath). */
  .library-galaxy svg[data-core-lightning] {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    pointer-events: none;
    overflow: visible;
    z-index: 25;
    mix-blend-mode: screen;
  }

  /* ── Light-mode lightning → subtle scientific connection line ──────
     The card→core bolt is built by universe-core-effects.ts as a
     triple-stroke jagged path (halo + mid + white-hot core) plus
     spark/flash circles, glowing through SVG blur filters and
     composited with `mix-blend-mode: screen`. That recipe is tuned
     for the dark cosmic stage; on the bright Knowledge Observatory it
     reads as loud, neon and game-like.

     This block re-skins ONLY light mode into a calm connection line.
     It is pure CSS over the JS-built nodes — the script is untouched:
     - every rule is gated on `html:not(.dark)`, so dark mode is
       byte-for-byte unchanged;
     - `stroke-width` / `filter` / the core's `stroke` are SVG
       presentation attributes → overridden by plain CSS;
     - `style.stroke` on the halo/mid layers is inline → needs
       `!important`; element `opacity` is deliberately left alone so
       the JS fade-out keeps working — the whole overlay is dimmed at
       the `<svg>` level instead, which the per-element fade scales.
     The effect stays hover-triggered and transient exactly as before
     — this changes how it looks, never when it fires.

     GOTCHA — each selector below is wrapped WHOLE in `:global(...)`.
     universe-core-effects.ts builds the bolt with `createElementNS`,
     so the <svg>, <path> and <circle> carry NO Astro scope hash. A
     normally-scoped rule (even one only prefixed with `:global(html
     ...)`) makes Astro append `[data-astro-cid-*]` to `.library-galaxy
     / svg / path / circle` — which then matches NOTHING. Wrapping the
     entire selector in `:global()` keeps it unscoped so it actually
     reaches the runtime-built nodes. */
  :global(html:not(.dark) .library-galaxy svg[data-core-lightning]) {
    /* Significant overall opacity cut. `screen` blend would make a
       mid-tone line vanish on a light surface, so it composites
       normally here. */
    opacity: 0.42;
    mix-blend-mode: normal;
  }
  /* Strokes — soft blue-gray instead of electric neon; thin, uniform,
     SVG glow filters removed, so it reads as a drawn connection line
     rather than a bolt. Blue-gray harmonises with the navy observatory
     ellipses instead of competing with them. */
  :global(html:not(.dark) .library-galaxy svg[data-core-lightning] path) {
    stroke: #7b8aa3 !important;
    stroke-width: 1.1;
    filter: none;
  }
  /* Spark + impact-flash circles are the most game-like part — drop
     them entirely in light mode so only the calm line remains. */
  :global(html:not(.dark) .library-galaxy svg[data-core-lightning] circle) {
    display: none;
  }

  /* Ambient backdrop — sits ABOVE the scene background, BELOW the UI.
     Self-contained starfield. */
  .library-ambient {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
    z-index: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  /* `.library-aurora` and `.library-nebula-*` rules removed: their
     markup nodes were retired when the unified page-level backdrop
     system in `.library-root` took over atmospheric coloring. */
  /* Starfield — a CSS-only matrix of tiny bright pixels rendered as
     a single repeating radial-gradient pattern. No DOM nodes, no JS.
     Two layers (small + medium) at slightly different offsets for
     parallax-like depth. */
  .library-starfield {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background-image:
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 20% 12%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 65% 24%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 35% 38%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 82% 47%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 12% 58%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 73% 67%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 28% 78%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1px 1px at 88% 88%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text) 50%, transparent 100%),
      /* Accent stars — all violet now. Cyan accents were swapped to
         purple to align with the page's violet-led palette and avoid
         out-of-key cyan dots on the cosmic field. */
      radial-gradient(1.5px 1.5px at 50% 18%, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1.5px 1.5px at 92% 32%, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1.5px 1.5px at 8% 72%, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple) 50%, transparent 100%),
      radial-gradient(1.5px 1.5px at 58% 92%, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple) 50%, transparent 100%);
    opacity: 0.40;
  }
  .library-root > :not(.library-ambient):not(.knowledge-scene-background) {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  /* ── Knowledge Observatory — light-mode-only decorative rings ──────
     Passive SVG layer: concentric "observatory" ellipses + tick marks
     (ry = 0.52 x rx, so they read as orbital tracks in a low-angle
     perspective and echo the carousel's elliptical orbit), centered on the carousel
     orbit center. It lives INSIDE
     `.library-galaxy`, so `top/left: 50%` + `translate(-50%, -50%)`
     resolves against the very same box the orbit cards center on
     (`.galaxy-card { top: 50%; left: 50% }`). The ring center therefore
     tracks the carousel center automatically at every breakpoint —
     desktop (relative stage + vertical offset) and mobile (fixed,
     viewport-centered stage) alike. No coordinate math is duplicated.

     Layering — z-index 0 within `.library-galaxy`:
       observatory (0) < orbit cards (2) < focus backdrop (15)
       < lightning (25) < focused card (30).
     The rings always sit behind the cards and the cards stay visually
     dominant. `pointer-events: none` keeps every click, hover, focus
     and route landing on the cards — never the rings — so the carousel
     logic is untouched.

     Light-mode only: `display: none` by default, flipped to `block`
     solely when <html> has no `.dark` class. Dark mode renders nothing,
     so the dark showcase is byte-for-byte unchanged. */
  .galaxy-observatory {
    --obs-size: clamp(460px, 56vw, 700px);
    position: absolute;
    top: 50%;
    left: 50%;
    width: var(--obs-size);
    height: var(--obs-size);
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    pointer-events: none;
    z-index: 0;
    display: none;
    opacity: 0.85;
    transition: opacity var(--yuval-galaxy-motion-normal, 280ms)
                var(--yuval-galaxy-ease-soft, ease);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-observatory {
    /* Hidden in light mode — the photographic day scene
       (`ai_researcher_workspace_day_bg.webp`) carries its own ambient
       depth, so this SVG ring layer would compete with it. Kept in
       the DOM so dark mode (which never matches `:not(.dark)`) is
       unaffected and the markup-driven aria layer stays stable. */
    display: none;
  }
  .obs-svg {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    display: block;
    overflow: visible;
  }
  /* Solid hairline rings — crisp at any scale via non-scaling-stroke. */
  .obs-ring {
    fill: none;
    stroke: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.16);
    stroke-width: 1.5px;
    vector-effect: non-scaling-stroke;
  }
  .obs-ring--outer { stroke: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.09); }
  /* Accent + fine rings are dotted (round-capped dashes); their stroke
     is allowed to scale so the dots read proportionally with the ring. */
  .obs-ring--accent {
    fill: none;
    stroke: rgba(14, 116, 144, 0.30);
    stroke-width: 2.4px;
    stroke-linecap: round;
    stroke-dasharray: 0.5 17;
  }
  .obs-ring--fine {
    fill: none;
    stroke: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.22);
    stroke-width: 1.9px;
    stroke-linecap: round;
    stroke-dasharray: 0.5 13;
  }
  .obs-cross {
    stroke: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.20);
    stroke-width: 1.5px;
    stroke-linecap: round;
    vector-effect: non-scaling-stroke;
  }
  .obs-dot        { fill: rgba(14, 116, 144, 0.42); }
  .obs-dot--minor { fill: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.30); }
  /* When a card is focused the rings fade back so they never clutter
     the area behind the enlarged center card. `data-galaxy-focused` is
     the existing flag set by universe-layout.ts — no JS is touched. */
  .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused] .galaxy-observatory {
    opacity: 0.42;
  }

  /* ── Light-mode carousel polish — card depth + motion ─────────────
     A focused polish pass for the orbit carousel in light mode only.
     Every rule here is scoped under `html:not(.dark)`, so the dark
     showcase is byte-for-byte unchanged. Three things are tuned:

       1. Card depth — light-mode book covers were reading as "pasted
          onto" the ivory background. A soft blue-gray drop-shadow plus
          a faint cyan edge light grounds each card in the space. The
          shadow follows the PNG alpha silhouette because the filter
          sits on the un-masked `.galaxy-card` wrapper, not a box.
       2. Position depth — the resting orbit reads as more spatial:
          the slot scale + opacity ramps are widened so front/near
          stations sit forward and far stations recede, without
          hiding content.
       3. Motion — the rotation transition swaps the mechanical
          Material curve for a smoother, gently inertial premium curve.

     The base-card drop-shadow is constant (not position-dependent) so
     the filtered layer rasterizes once and merely translates during a
     drag; depth separation is carried by the scale/opacity ramp. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-card {
    /* Light mode lifts the depth opacity floor — far cards stay a
       touch more present against the bright ivory field than in dark
       mode (0.62 vs 0.55). Scale + z-index depth come from the
       per-breakpoint base rule and are shared with dark mode. */
    --slot-opacity: calc(0.62 + 0.38 * var(--orbit-depth, 0.5));
    /* Soft blue-gray shadow (contact + ambient) + barely-there cyan
       edge light. Constant, so the filtered layer rasterizes once;
       the depth opacity ramp above fades the shadow on far cards for
       free (a lower element opacity dims its own drop-shadow). No
       heavy blur — the cards stay crisp. */
    filter:
      drop-shadow(0 5px 12px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.15))
      drop-shadow(0 1px 3px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.12))
      drop-shadow(0 0 2px rgba(14, 116, 144, 0.14));
  }
  /* Focused (centered) card stays dominant — a slightly deeper soft
     shadow and a touch more cyan edge glow. Values are intentionally
     moderate: the centered card is transform-scaled, which enlarges
     the rendered shadow along with it. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] {
    filter:
      drop-shadow(0 6px 16px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.18))
      drop-shadow(0 1px 4px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.13))
      drop-shadow(0 0 2px rgba(14, 116, 144, 0.20));
  }

  /* ── Light-mode navigation controls — glass rotate pill ───────────
     The bottom rotate arrows read as soft glass controls in daylight:
     translucent warm-white fill, hairline border, soft shadow and a
     dark-navy icon. Scoped to light mode; the dark control styling in
     the media-query blocks below is untouched. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-orbit-controls {
    background: rgba(255, 253, 249, 0.62);
    border-color: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.14);
    box-shadow: 0 4px 16px -6px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.22);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-orbit-btn {
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text);
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.70);
    border-color: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.12);
    box-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.12);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-orbit-btn:hover,
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-orbit-btn:focus-visible {
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text);
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
    border-color: rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.24);
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px -2px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.20);
  }

  /* ── Day-mode chrome cleanup — kill dark-mode leftovers ───────────
     A few pieces of chrome were styled with hard black drop shadows
     that belong to the dark showcase and read as "stuck-on" panels in
     the bright observatory. Re-cast their shadows as the same soft
     blue-gray used by the cards and the rotate pill. Light mode only;
     every other surface keeps its theme-aware tokens. */
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-other-knowledge {
    box-shadow: 0 8px 22px -10px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.22);
  }
  :global(html:not(.dark)) .series-details-drawer {
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 20%, transparent) inset,
      -24px 0 60px -10px rgba(30, 45, 80, 0.22);
  }

  /* ── Mobile baseline: linear stack, ordered to the spec.
        The desktop wrapper aside/main elements are passthrough on mobile —
        their children unfurl in the natural document order, then `order:`
        re-shuffles them into the discovery sequence. ─────────────────── */
  .library-body {
    max-width: 1280px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  /* On mobile the wrapper aside/main elements are not layout containers;
     reset their flex behaviour and let their children act as siblings. */
  .lb-area-stage,
  .lb-area-right {
    display: contents;
  }

  /* ── Mobile content area ──────────────────────────────────────────
     `.lb-area-featured` (galaxy orbit stage) is visible on mobile too,
     scaled down proportionally — see CLAUDE.md "same orbit composition
     on mobile". The mobile-specific orbit sizing lives in the
     `@media (max-width: 1023px)` block further below.
     `.lb-area-quick-mobile` is a legacy slot for an AI assistant /
     quick-actions row that is currently suppressed. */
  .lb-area-quick-mobile {
    display: none;
  }

  /* ── LibraryHero — strip the legacy card chrome ─────────────────
     The legacy mobile + tablet LibraryHero rendered as a discrete
     card with border, panel background, blur and overflow:hidden
     (which clipped the nowrap title when the central area got
     narrow and a fixed side panel encroached on the right edge).
     The user wants only the welcome text (eyebrow + title +
     subtitle) framed by the cosmic page, not by a panel — the same
     identity as the desktop hero strip. Override applies at every
     viewport below the desktop dashboard (≤1023px). Desktop
     (≥1024px) strips chrome via LibraryHero's own @media rule. */
  /* ── Series glow pulse ────────────────────────────────────────────
        One-shot 3-second multi-colour border + halo applied to every
        card that belongs to a series. Triggered (1) when the user
        clicks "Show series items" inside the focused series capsule,
        and (2) when the user hovers a series capsule in the resting
        orbit without focusing it. Works on every viewport because the
        keyframes live outside any @media block. */
  @keyframes yuval-series-glow {
    0%, 100% {
      box-shadow: var(--yuval-galaxy-card-shadow);
      border-color: var(--yuval-galaxy-card-border);
    }
    12% {
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(250, 204, 21, 0.95),
        0 0 28px 6px rgba(250, 204, 21, 0.55);
      border-color: rgba(250, 204, 21, 0.95);
    }
    37% {
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.95),
        0 0 28px 6px rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.55);
      border-color: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.95);
    }
    62% {
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(168, 85, 247, 0.95),
        0 0 28px 6px rgba(168, 85, 247, 0.55);
      border-color: rgba(168, 85, 247, 0.95);
    }
    87% {
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.95),
        0 0 28px 6px rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.55);
      border-color: rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.95);
    }
  }
  .galaxy-card.is-series-glow :global(.lc) {
    animation: yuval-series-glow 3s ease-out 1;
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .galaxy-card.is-series-glow :global(.lc) { animation: none; }
  }

  @media (max-width: 1023px) {
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh) {
      /* No top padding — the hero text should land right under the
         header line. Side + bottom paddings keep modest breathing
         around the text block. */
      padding: 0 0.5rem 0.75rem;
      background-color: transparent;
      border: 0;
      backdrop-filter: none;
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: none;
      box-shadow: none;
      overflow: visible;
      text-align: center;
    }
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-halo) {
      display: none;
    }
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-header) {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      text-align: center;
      gap: 0;
      margin-block-end: 0.25rem;
    }
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-text) {
      text-align: center;
    }
    /* Eyebrow: cyan→violet gradient text in mixed case, matching the
       desktop hero. Overrides the mobile baseline (uppercase + grey)
       which clashed with the cosmic look once the panel chrome was
       removed. */
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-eyebrow) {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      text-transform: none;
      font-weight: 500;
      font-size: 0.8125rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      margin-block-end: 0.3125rem;
      background: linear-gradient(
        90deg,
        var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-cyan) 0%,
        var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple) 100%);
      background-clip: text;
      -webkit-background-clip: text;
      color: transparent;
      -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
    }
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-title) {
      line-height: 1.05;
      margin-block-end: 0.375rem;
    }
    :global(.lb-area-hero .lh-subtitle) {
      margin-inline: auto;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      line-height: 1.4;
    }

    /* ── Mobile orbit — same composition as desktop, scaled down ─────
       The user asked for the SAME orbit (every readable item on its
       own station around the central core) on phone + tablet, just
       smaller. We re-show the featured section (hidden globally by the
       base reset), then re-declare the orbit positioning rules with
       smaller card width + smaller ellipse radii. The math is identical
       to the desktop rule inside `@media (min-width: 1024px)`. */
    /* Orbit always centered on the viewport's central book icon.
       The icon lives in `.knowledge-scene-background` (position:fixed)
       and sits a few pixels above the viewport's exact middle. To
       guarantee the orbit center (`.galaxy-card { top: 50% }` of
       `.library-galaxy`) lands ON that icon at EVERY screen size, we
       pin the galaxy box to the viewport with position:fixed and
       center it with top:50% + transform translate(-50%, -50%). The
       orbit cards are inside this fixed box, so they automatically
       sit in concentric ellipses around the icon — regardless of how
       tall the hero text grew or what other content stacks above. */
    .lb-area-featured {
      display: block;
      /* This wrapper no longer needs to host the orbit — it just
         remains in flow as a placeholder so the hero text spacing
         doesn't collapse. The actual galaxy lives in a fixed layer. */
    }

    .library-galaxy {
      position: fixed;
      /* Mobile orbit anchored to the boundary between the middle and
         the bottom third of the viewport (Tomer: "בין שליש תחתון
         לשליש שני"). Center sits at 2/3 of the viewport (≈66.66dvh)
         so the orbit body straddles the line — upper stations in the
         middle third, lower stations in the bottom third. The orbit
         no longer aligns with the background galaxy image's book icon;
         that's intentional, the carousel is now a discrete lower-
         anchored surface rather than a stage centerpiece. */
      top: calc(200dvh / 3);
      left: 50%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      display: block;
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 100vw;
      min-height: clamp(320px, 60vw, 480px);
      margin: 0;
      overflow: visible;
      padding: 0;
      z-index: 1;
      /* Drag-to-rotate uses pointermove on the stage. Without
         `touch-action: none` the browser keeps ownership of horizontal
         swipes (treats them as pan / overscroll), and pointermove never
         fires on touch devices — so rotating cards by dragging silently
         fails on mobile. The page is overflow:hidden anyway, so we lose
         nothing by claiming the gesture for JS. Taps/clicks still fire
         normally on the cards and rotate buttons. */
      touch-action: none;
      /* The orbit math (cos/sin) is direction-agnostic via --galaxy-dir
         (set inline on the element in markup). Setting `direction: ltr`
         here keeps absolute positioning consistent; per-card content
         still picks up page direction via `.galaxy-card { direction: var(--page-direction, ltr); }` below. */
      direction: ltr;
    }

    /* ── Observatory — phone tuning ───────────────────────────────────
       Smaller footprint, dimmer strokes, and the fine-detail group +
       the faint outer ring dropped entirely. Keeps the rings a subtle
       whisper behind the orbit and clear of the focused card and the
       bottom rotate controls (CLAUDE.md: "reduce observatory detail,
       keep rings subtle" on mobile). */
    .galaxy-observatory {
      --obs-size: clamp(250px, 74vw, 380px);
      opacity: 0.5;
    }
    .obs-ring--outer,
    .obs-detail {
      display: none;
    }
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused] .galaxy-observatory {
      opacity: 0.26;
    }

    .galaxy-card {
      position: absolute;
      flex: initial;
      max-width: none;
      /* Card width shrinks proportionally to viewport. Sized 25% larger
         than the previous mobile values per Tomer's request: the cover
         art now carries baked-in mobile typography (front-mobile.png),
         and the larger cards let that artwork read clearly without an
         overlay label. Floor: 120px (legible on 360px phones). Cap:
         175px (still safely under the desktop 190px peer at 1024px).
         Exposed as `--card-base-width` so the focused-state scale rule
         below can target an exact viewport-relative size (70vw) without
         re-deriving the clamp by hand. The series capsule overrides
         this variable for its slightly wider footprint. */
      --card-base-width: clamp(120px, 27.5vw, 175px);
      width: var(--card-base-width);
      cursor: pointer;
      top: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      /* Tighter ellipse on mobile so the orbit's lower edge clears
         the rotate-controls pill at the viewport bottom with a clear
         safety gap (not just touching). orbit-ry shrunk again from
         18vh→13vh, and the floor/ceiling tightened in tandem. */
      --orbit-rx: clamp(110px, 38vw, 220px);
      --orbit-ry: clamp(70px, 13vh, 105px);
      --orbit-active-angle: calc(var(--orbit-angle, 0deg) + var(--orbit-rotation, 0deg));
      /* Upper arc = near/front, lower arc = far/back (`1 - sin`), same
         inverted depth model as desktop. */
      --orbit-depth: calc((1 - sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg))) / 2);
      /* Gentler depth ramp than desktop — phone cards are already
         small, so far stations only step down to 0.80 scale / 0.62
         opacity. Keeps satellites readable, not overcrowded. */
      --slot-scale: calc(0.80 + 0.20 * var(--orbit-depth));
      --slot-opacity: calc(0.62 + 0.38 * var(--orbit-depth));
      --tilt: calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * 4deg * var(--galaxy-dir, 1) * -1);
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(
          calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-rx) * var(--galaxy-dir, 1)),
          calc(sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-ry))
        )
        rotate(var(--tilt))
        scale(var(--slot-scale));
      opacity: var(--slot-opacity);
      transition:
        transform var(--orbit-motion-duration, 600ms)
                  var(--orbit-motion-ease, cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1)),
        opacity var(--orbit-motion-duration, 600ms)
                var(--orbit-motion-ease, cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1));
      /* Depth-sorted stacking, same as desktop: 2 (back) .. 10 (front). */
      z-index: calc(2 + var(--orbit-depth) * 8);
      direction: var(--page-direction, ltr);
    }

    /* Light-mode phone tuning — a lighter card shadow than desktop:
       smaller blur, no cyan edge, to keep compositing cheap and the
       bright scene uncluttered. Overrides the non-media light-mode
       `.galaxy-card` filter above (same specificity, declared later
       and inside a matching media query). */
    :global(html:not(.dark)) .galaxy-card {
      filter:
        drop-shadow(0 3px 8px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.16))
        drop-shadow(0 1px 2px rgba(34, 52, 92, 0.12));
    }

    /* Series capsule a touch wider than a book card, same ratio as desktop.
       Scaled 25% alongside the book/lesson cards above. Overrides
       `--card-base-width` so the focused-scale math below uses the
       series footprint rather than the book/lesson one. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"] {
      --card-base-width: clamp(135px, 31.25vw, 195px);
      --series-color-resolved: var(--series-color, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-gold, #c9a96e));
    }

    /* Per-kind accent tint — books gold, lessons cyan, course violet.
       Sets a CSS variable that the inner LibraryCard reads for its
       accent strip; same contract as desktop. */
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="book"]   { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-gold); }
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="lesson"] { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-cyan); }
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="course"] { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple); }

    /* Drag-to-rotate: kill the transform transition while a drag is
       in flight so the carousel tracks the cursor in real time. */
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-dragging] .galaxy-card {
      transition: none;
      cursor: grabbing;
    }

    /* Block the browser's native image-drag ghost on every card and
       on its descendant artwork so pointermove tracking stays smooth. */
    .galaxy-card,
    .galaxy-card *,
    .galaxy-card img,
    .galaxy-card svg {
      -webkit-user-drag: none;
    }

    /* Galaxy orbit controls (rotate ←/→ buttons) on mobile — pinned
       to the bottom of the viewport so they stay clear of the orbit /
       carousel and remain easy to tap. Self-contained pill styling
       (flex + background + border + blur) lives here because the
       desktop @media block below isn't reached on phones; without it
       the wrapper falls back to display:block and stretches across
       the viewport. z-index sits above the focused card (z:30) so the
       buttons never get covered by an enlarged centered card. */
    .galaxy-orbit-controls {
      /* Always pinned to the very bottom of the viewport on mobile.
         Only the iOS home-indicator safe-area-inset-bottom is added
         on top — no extra cosmetic offset — so the buttons hug the
         screen edge as the user requested. */
      position: fixed !important;
      inset-block-end: auto;
      bottom: env(safe-area-inset-bottom, 0px) !important;
      left: 0;
      right: 0;
      margin-inline: auto;
      display: flex;
      width: max-content;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.3125rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12);
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.18),
        0 6px 18px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.30);
      backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      z-index: 40;
      direction: ltr;
    }
    .galaxy-orbit-btn {
      /* Compact rotate control — small pearl glass circle with a clear
         icon, slightly more visible than the previous muted version. */
      width: 30px;
      height: 30px;
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      border-radius: 50%;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.10);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.22);
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.28),
        0 2px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.24);
      cursor: pointer;
      padding: 0;
      transition: color 0.15s ease, background-color 0.15s ease,
                  border-color 0.15s ease, transform 0.15s ease;
    }
    .galaxy-orbit-btn:hover,
    .galaxy-orbit-btn:focus-visible {
      color: #ffffff;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.18);
      border-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.36);
      outline: none;
    }
    [dir="rtl"] .galaxy-orbit-btn svg { transform: scaleX(-1); }

    /* ── Mobile focus state (mirror of desktop) ────────────────────
       All the focus-state CSS — centered card scaling, galaxy CTA
       slot, reading-entry overlay panel — lives inside the desktop
       `@media (min-width: 1024px)` block below, so on mobile none of
       those rules apply. Without this duplication a tap on a mobile
       orbit card doesn't visibly scale it, and the reading-entry
       `<a>` + close `<button>` render at default styling, polluting
       the screen with their text under every card.

       This block replays just enough of the desktop rules to give
       mobile the same "tap card → scales up, X close button appears,
       reading-entry panel sits flush below the cover" behavior. */

    /* Focused card flies UP out of the orbit and lands just below the
       hero text ("כל הידע שלך…"), per Tomer's request:
         "הכרטיס יצא ממקומו באנימציה, יופיע על המסך ממש מתחת למילים".
       Geometry:
         - Orbit center sits at `calc(200dvh / 3)` ≈ 66.66dvh (see
           `.library-galaxy` mobile rule above).
         - The card scales to 70vw wide; a typical 2:3 book cover ends
           up ≈ 60dvh tall after the scale.
         - Translating the card up by 18dvh (in viewport units, applied
           AFTER the scale — leftmost in the transform list means
           applied LAST in CSS composition order) lands its centre at
           ≈ 48.66dvh, so the card's top edge sits a hair below the
           hero subtitle (~22dvh) on common phone heights. The
           reading-entry overlay child follows because it lives inside
           the same `.galaxy-card` transform.
       The existing `transition: transform 600ms …` on `.galaxy-card`
       drives the animation between orbit position and this new
       above-orbit resting spot — no JS change required.
       Counter-scaled descendants (`.reading-entry-overlay`,
       `.galaxy-cta`) continue to multiply by `cbw / 70vw` to hold
       their authored size; they're unaffected by the outer
       translateY since translation is uniform, not magnified by
       scale. */
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] {
      transform:
        translateY(-18dvh)
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        scale(calc(70vw / var(--card-base-width)));
      opacity: 1;
      z-index: 30;
      cursor: default;
    }

    /* Mobile non-centre recede — the desktop counterpart at
       `.library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused] .galaxy-card:not([data-pos="center"])`
       lives inside `@media (min-width: 1024px)` so it never reaches
       phones. Duplicated here with gentler values: mobile cards sit
       closer to the viewport edges and aggressive blur/dim reads as
       harsh on a small screen.

       Specificity (0, 4, 0) wins over the mobile `.galaxy-card` (0, 1, 0)
       opacity rule, so `var(--slot-opacity)` is correctly overridden.
       `scale` is the individual CSS property (not `transform: scale`)
       so it composes with the orbit's cos/sin transform without us
       having to recompute coordinates. Trigger is `data-galaxy-focused`,
       set by universe-layout.ts when any card is centred — same flag
       as desktop, no carousel-logic changes. */
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused]
      .galaxy-card:not([data-pos="center"]) {
      filter: blur(2px) saturate(0.85);
      opacity: 0.42;
      scale: 0.9;
      transition:
        filter 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        opacity 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        scale 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
    }

    /* Reduced motion: skip the recede entirely on mobile too. The
       desktop reduced-motion guard at line ~3077 lives inside the
       desktop media block, so phones need their own. */
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused]
        .galaxy-card:not([data-pos="center"]) {
        transition: none;
        scale: 1;
        filter: none;
        opacity: var(--slot-opacity);
      }
    }

    /* On mobile we drop the open-orb + X-close cluster — Tomer asked to
       remove the X next to the focused card. Closing is handled by
       tapping outside the card / tapping another orbit station. The
       `.galaxy-cta` wrapper itself stays visible so its only remaining
       contents — the series action pills (Show items / Details) — can
       sit at the bottom of the focused series card on mobile too. */
    .galaxy-cta-open,
    .galaxy-cta-open-label,
    .galaxy-cta-close {
      display: none !important;
    }
    /* Mobile placement for the series action pills — mirrors the desktop
       rules at the bottom of this stylesheet so the wrapper has the same
       positioning context on every viewport. Lifted into the mobile block
       because the desktop `.galaxy-cta` rule lives inside
       `@media (min-width: 1024px)` and would otherwise leave the mobile
       wrapper unstyled (in-flow, always visible). */
    .galaxy-cta {
      position: absolute;
      top: 66%;
      left: 50%;
      bottom: auto;
      right: auto;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      transition: opacity 0.25s ease 0.15s;
      z-index: 2;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] .galaxy-cta {
      opacity: 1;
      pointer-events: auto;
      /* Counter-scale against the focused card's mobile scale
         (`scale(70vw / var(--card-base-width))`). Without this the
         pills inherit the card magnification and render ~1.7× too
         big with oversized font. Multiplying by the inverse keeps
         the pills at their authored visual size on every phone. */
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%) scale(calc(var(--card-base-width) / 70vw));
    }
    /* Mobile-only shrink for the series action pills. The counter-scale
       above keeps them at authored size, but authored is still too tall
       for a phone (Tomer reported huge / out-of-proportion buttons on
       mobile). Tighten padding, font and icon dimensions specifically
       inside the mobile block so the pills read as compact chips under
       the focused series card. */
    .galaxy-cta-series-actions { gap: 0.3rem; }
    .galaxy-cta-series-btn {
      padding: 0.25rem 0.55rem;
      font-size: 0.625rem;
      gap: 0.3rem;
      letter-spacing: 0;
    }
    .galaxy-cta-series-btn-icon {
      width: 12px;
      height: 12px;
    }
    /* Image-based reading-entry panel — mobile equivalent of the
       desktop CTA. The visual base IS `reading-entry-card1.png`. The
       title, subtitle, summary pill and meta row all live INSIDE the
       panel. FULL counter-scale (cbw/70vw) neutralises the focused
       card's 70vw/cbw scale so spec px values map 1:1 to visible
       pixels. */
    .reading-entry-overlay {
      position: absolute;
      left: 50%;
      /* 14px visible gap below the cover. With FULL counter-scale the
         spec value applies 1:1. */
      top: calc(100% - 14px);
      width: 92vw;
      max-width: 390px;
      /* Height bumped from 190 → 220 so the new summary pill + meta
         row fit cleanly without clipping at the bottom. */
      height: 220px;
      border-radius: 22px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      transform:
        translate(-50%, 0)
        scale(calc(var(--card-base-width) / 70vw));
      transform-origin: top center;
      display: block;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      border: 0;
      background: transparent;
      color: inherit;
      -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
      opacity: 0;
      visibility: hidden;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 30;
      transition:
        transform 180ms ease,
        filter 180ms ease,
        opacity 240ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        visibility 0s linear 240ms;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] .reading-entry-overlay {
      opacity: 1;
      visibility: visible;
      pointer-events: auto;
      transition:
        transform 180ms ease,
        filter 180ms ease,
        opacity 240ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        visibility 0s linear 0s;
    }
    .reading-entry-main {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      display: block;
      border-radius: 22px;
      background: transparent;
      color: inherit;
      text-decoration: none;
      cursor: pointer;
      z-index: 1;
      -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
    }
    .reading-entry-main:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
    }
    .reading-entry-asset {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      border-radius: 22px;
      background-image: url('/assets/ui/reading-entry/reading-entry-card1.png');
      background-size: 100% 100%;
      background-repeat: no-repeat;
      background-position: center;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 2;
      transition:
        transform 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        box-shadow 220ms ease,
        filter 220ms ease;
    }
    .reading-entry-text {
      position: absolute;
      left: 50%;
      top: 58%;
      width: 94%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: 7px;
      text-align: center;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 3;
      font-family:
        'Heebo', 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system,
        'Segoe UI', 'Noto Sans Hebrew', sans-serif;
    }
    .reading-entry-title {
      font-size: 25px;
      font-weight: 700;
      line-height: 1.05;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.96);
      text-shadow:
        0 0 10px rgba(120, 180, 255, 0.30),
        0 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      margin: 0;
      max-width: 100%;
      overflow: hidden;
      text-overflow: ellipsis;
      white-space: nowrap;
    }
    .reading-entry-subtitle {
      font-size: 14px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1.2;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72);
      text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.45);
      margin: 0;
      max-width: 100%;
      overflow: hidden;
      text-overflow: ellipsis;
      white-space: nowrap;
    }
    /* Mobile summary pill — slightly smaller than desktop so it stays
       quietly secondary on a phone. `pointer-events: auto` re-opts the
       pill into hit-testing while the rest of `.reading-entry-text`
       passes taps through to `.reading-entry-main`. */
    .reading-entry-summary-pill {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      height: 24px;
      padding: 0 12px;
      margin: 1px 0 0;
      border-radius: 999px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      font-size: 11.5px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1;
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
      color: rgba(245, 250, 255, 0.92);
      background: rgba(8, 18, 40, 0.55);
      border: 1px solid rgba(120, 175, 235, 0.42);
      text-decoration: none;
      text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      pointer-events: auto;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition:
        background 160ms ease,
        border-color 160ms ease,
        transform 160ms ease;
    }
    .reading-entry-summary-pill:active {
      transform: scale(0.97);
      background: rgba(18, 32, 60, 0.7);
    }
    /* Very small phones (≤360px): tighten panel + text so nothing
       clips in the in-panel layout. */
    @media (max-width: 360px) {
      .reading-entry-overlay {
        width: 94vw;
        height: 208px;
      }
      .reading-entry-title    { font-size: 23px; }
      .reading-entry-subtitle { font-size: 13px; }
      .reading-entry-summary-pill {
        height: 22px;
        padding: 0 11px;
        font-size: 11px;
      }
    }
    /* Hover is desktop-only per the spec — mobile keeps just the
       press-in scale + brightness so taps still feel responsive. */
    .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:active) {
      transform:
        translate(-50%, 0)
        scale(calc((var(--card-base-width) / 70vw) * 0.985));
      filter: brightness(1.04);
    }

    /* Standalone extras wrapper, secondary link and section label are
       retired in this design — the meta row now lives INSIDE the
       reading-entry panel itself. They are kept in the DOM only for
       a11y back-compat. */
    .center-card-extras,
    .cc-secondary-link,
    .cc-meta-label {
      display: none;
    }
    /* In-panel lesson meta row — bottom child of `.reading-entry-text`
       on mobile too. Inherits the panel's counter-scale + centered
       axis; chips are tightened to fit the narrower phone width. */
    .cc-meta {
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: row;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 6px;
      font-family:
        'Heebo', 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system,
        'Segoe UI', 'Noto Sans Hebrew', sans-serif;
    }
    .cc-meta-item {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      height: 26px;
      padding: 0 10px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      font-size: 12px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1;
      color: rgba(235, 242, 255, 0.92);
      white-space: nowrap;
      background: rgba(8, 18, 40, 0.55);
      border: 1px solid rgba(130, 180, 240, 0.28);
      text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
    }
    /* Disable the legacy middot separator. */
    .cc-meta-item + .cc-meta-item::before {
      content: none;
    }
  }

  /* Small-screen baseline for the orbit scene's vertical offset. The
     orbit itself is hidden below 1024px (see `.lb-area-featured` above),
     but the variable is defined here so the responsive ladder
     (32 → 56 → 72) is complete at every breakpoint. The transform is
     applied on `.library-galaxy` inside the 1024+ query, so a parent
     transform never affects mobile layout. */
  .library-galaxy {
    --orbit-vertical-offset: 32px;
    /* Carousel rotation motion — a smoother, slightly inertial premium
       curve so stations glide through the knowledge space instead of
       snapping between positions. Consumed by the orbit-card transform
       + opacity transition in both light and dark mode. */
    --orbit-motion-duration: 600ms;
    --orbit-motion-ease: cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1);
  }
  /* Reduced motion: collapse the rotation duration so depth changes
     apply instantly. The global theme.css rule already neutralises the
     transition property; this keeps the token itself consistent for
     anything that reads it inside a calc(). */
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .library-galaxy { --orbit-motion-duration: 1ms; }
  }

  /* ── Tablet (≥640px): same mobile flow, more inline padding ──
        Top padding kept tight so the hero text remains close to the
        header line. Inline + bottom paddings grow for breathing
        room around the wider viewport. */
  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .library-root { padding: 0.5rem 1.5rem 4rem; }
  }

  /* ── Desktop (≥1024px): ONE viewport dashboard, no long scroll ───── */
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .library-root {
      /* Block padding owns top/bottom rhythm. Inline padding is
         SYMMETRIC so `.library-body` (max-width + margin: 0 auto)
         centers ITSELF on the viewport — that gives the galaxy core
         (which sits at the visual center of the body) a perfectly
         viewport-centered anchor. The clamp value also clears the
         FloatingSidebar at the inline-end side (rail width ~92px
         + ~16px gap from edge). Independent from this: the two
         support panels (ContinueLearningCard + LibraryStatsPanel)
         are `position: fixed` from inside their own components and
         anchor directly to the viewport edge via `inset-inline-start: 20px`,
         so their 20px gap stays constant regardless of this padding. */
      /* Top padding tightened (1.25rem → 0.25rem) so the desktop
         hero strip sits right under the sticky header line — same
         preference applied on mobile. The galaxy stage below the
         hero now picks up the freed vertical space and the central
         core's vertical position is governed by --orbit-vertical-
         offset rather than by this padding. */
      padding-block-start: 0.25rem;
      padding-block-end: 1.5rem;
      padding-inline: clamp(60px, 8vw, 120px);
      /* Viewport math is owned by LibraryLayout — the layout sets
         --library-dashboard-min-height = calc(100dvh - --library-header-offset)
         on the slot wrapper, so the page does not have to know the
         header's pixel height. */
      min-height: var(--library-dashboard-min-height, 100dvh);
      /* Desktop layered backdrop, FIRST listed = TOP of the stack.
         Calibrated to the sampled asset palette: every layer either
         uses one of the sampled navy tones or stays a small violet
         accent centered on the stage. Hero + side accents were
         removed (asset isn't violet there).
         1. vignette        — corner darkening with sampled #000010
         2. primary accent  — small violet halo at the stage center
         3. secondary fade  — bottom navy continuation (#000010)
         The base color var(--yuval-galaxy-bg) (#01051b) sits beneath. */
      background-image:
        var(--yuval-galaxy-bg-vignette),
        var(--yuval-galaxy-bg-radial-primary),
        var(--yuval-galaxy-bg-radial-secondary);
    }

    /* Full-page atmospheric underlay removed: it placed a blurred copy
       of the asset under the whole page, which created a non-uniform
       halo right under where the central image sits — the eye then
       read the contrast between halo-area and rest as a rectangle
       outline, even after the asset's edges were faded. The flat
       page-bg color (#0a0a1f on .library-root above) plus the
       existing radial gradients + vignette are now the only
       atmospheric layers. */

    /* Re-enable real flex container on the center stage main.
       `.lb-area-right` stays as `display: contents` (inherited from the
       mobile baseline) — its only child `.lb-area-quick-mobile` is
       `display: none` on desktop, so the aside contributes nothing
       to the grid. The desktop floating rail lives outside the grid
       entirely (`<FloatingSidebar>` with `position: fixed`). The two
       support panels (ContinueLearningCard + LibraryStatsPanel) also
       live outside the grid via `position: fixed` from inside their
       own components. */
    .lb-area-stage {
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
    }

    /* Reset mobile order — explicit grid placement takes over. */
    .lb-area-hero,
    .lb-area-featured,
    .lb-area-quick-mobile { order: initial; }

    /* Restore the orbit stage that the mobile baseline hid above.
       `.lb-area-hero` no longer needs an explicit restore here
       because the mobile baseline keeps it visible (the hero text
       is shown on mobile too — see the override block below). */
    .lb-area-featured     { display: block; }

    /* 2-column dashboard with LANGUAGE-AWARE column placement:
         column 1 = inline-start  → outer support sidebar (continue +
                                    stats), on the side WHERE reading
                                    starts (visual-right in RTL Hebrew,
                                    visual-left in LTR English)
         column 2 = inline-end    → galaxy stage (center of the page),
                                    on the side opposite to where the
                                    document flow starts
       The narrow rail no longer claims a grid column — the desktop
       FloatingSidebar lives outside the grid as `position: fixed`,
       pinned to the inline-end edge of the viewport. The body adds
       a `padding-inline-end` gutter so the support sidebar doesn't
       collide with the floating rail.
       In LTR: support is visual-left, floating rail is visual-right
               (stage sits between sidebar and rail).
       In RTL: support is visual-right, floating rail is visual-left
               (same relationship, mirrored).
       No physical-direction lock. Grid resolves natively to the
       page's `dir` attribute. */
    .library-body {
      /* Single-column body — the two support panels are taken OUT of
         the body's flow (each is `position: fixed` from inside its
         own component CSS). No inline padding here: the SYMMETRIC
         inline padding lives on `.library-root` instead, so the body's
         max-width + margin: 0 auto centers it perfectly on the
         viewport. The galaxy core (image centered at left:50% of
         `.library-galaxy` inside the body) thus lands exactly at the
         viewport's center — independent of where the fixed support
         panels sit. */
      display: block;
      min-height: calc(var(--library-dashboard-min-height, 100dvh) - 2.75rem);
      max-width: 1440px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 0;
    }
    /* Galaxy stage still uses physical left/right for the absolute
       orbit slots so the TL/TR/ML/MR/BL/BR placement of the floating
       cards is language-independent (the slots target visual corners,
       not reading-flow corners). Cards inside re-apply page direction
       so Hebrew titles still read RTL. */
    .library-galaxy { direction: ltr; }
    .galaxy-card    { direction: var(--page-direction, ltr); }

    /* The two support panels (ContinueLearningCard + LibraryStatsPanel)
       are anchored individually via `position: fixed` from inside
       their own component CSS — ContinueLearningCard on the
       inline-start edge, LibraryStatsPanel on the inline-end edge,
       both at top: header-offset + 20px. They frame the carousel
       from opposite sides. No wrapper needed here. */

    /* ── Center stage: hero + galaxy ──────────────────────────────── */
    .lb-area-stage {
      /* Zero stage-gap: the hero now lives as the title strip of the
         galaxy, not a separate block. .galaxy-stage provides its own
         interior padding for the orbits. */
      gap: 0;
      min-width: 0;
      position: relative;
      /* No background layer here. The page-level unified system
         (--yuval-galaxy-bg-radial-primary on .library-root) is centered
         right under this column and provides the violet field for both
         hero and stage. Adding a column-level layer here used to
         compound the violet and produce a "block within a block" feel. */
    }
    .lb-area-hero {
      flex: 0 0 auto;
      max-width: 680px;
      margin-inline: auto;
      width: 100%;
    }
    /* Galaxy stage takes the remaining vertical space — with the
       recommendations strip removed, the orbit owns the entire lower
       half of the viewport so the central knowledge core can breathe. */
    .lb-area-featured {
      flex: 1 1 auto;
      min-height: 0;
      position: relative;
    }

    /* ── Mobile quick-actions aside: hidden on desktop ──
       The aside stays as `display: contents` (mobile baseline). Its
       only child `.lb-area-quick-mobile` is `display: none` on desktop,
       so the aside contributes nothing visible to the grid. The
       desktop floating rail is `<FloatingSidebar>` rendered outside
       `.library-body` with `position: fixed`. */
    .lb-area-quick-mobile { display: none; }

    /* Galaxy stage on desktop: absolute canvas anchored to the stage.
       Min-height bumped to 540 so the ML/MR orbit cards have enough
       vertical room not to overlap the central core at the narrowest
       desktop widths (1024-1199px).

       Background tuned to match the asset palette: a soft violet
       radial glow at the center fading to the page's deep navy at
       the edges. This is the primary fix for the "rectangle pasted
       in" look — the stage no longer has hard color contrast where
       the asset ends; the violet center seamlessly continues the
       asset's own glow, and the dark edges seamlessly continue the
       page background. */
    .library-galaxy {
      position: relative;
      display: block;
      height: 100%;
      min-height: 540px;
      margin: 0;
      overflow: visible;
      flex-direction: initial;
      scroll-snap-type: none;
      padding: 0;
      scrollbar-width: auto;
      scrollbar-color: auto;
      /* Vertical offset of the entire orbit scene (rings, central core,
         floating cards, glow, rotation controls) so rotated carousel
         items never overlap the page title above. Lives on the orbit
         container only — page title, breadcrumb, side panels and grid
         shell are unaffected. Responsive steps below override the value
         per breakpoint; the transform itself stays the same.
         Bumped to 90px (was 36px) so the TOP of the top-of-orbit cards
         always has at least ~20px of breathing room from the hero
         subtitle on every common 1024px+ viewport.
         Reduced from 90→50 (paired with --orbit-ry shrinking by the
         same ~40px) so the orbit becomes shorter on desktop while the
         TOP of the carousel stays at the same Y as before. */
      --orbit-vertical-offset: 50px;
      transform: translateY(var(--orbit-vertical-offset));
    }
    /* The earlier `.library-galaxy::before` underlay halo and
       `.galaxy-stage-veil` overlay were experimental edge-blending
       layers. Both removed: the new full-page actual-asset underlay
       on `.library-root::before` propagates the asset's visual
       language across the entire screen, so per-asset edge blending
       layers are no longer necessary. */
    .library-galaxy::-webkit-scrollbar { height: auto; }

    /* `.galaxy-core` and its child rules (.galaxy-core-pool,
       .galaxy-core-aura) were removed alongside their markup nodes:
       they were sized for a 240×240 CSS-rendered core, but the asset
       is 760-820px wide and covered them entirely. They contributed
       nothing visible. The asset + page-level unified backdrop is
       the entire central composition. */

    /* The galaxy PNG no longer lives inside the orbit stage; it is
       now rendered once at the page root as `.knowledge-scene-background`
       (full-viewport fixed). Edge mask, max-width, focus-dim and
       reduced-motion rules that targeted `.galaxy-stage-image` were
       removed alongside the markup. */

    /* ── Floating cards: elliptical orbit.
          Every readable item has its own station along an ellipse around
          the central area. Position is computed in CSS via cos()/sin()
          from each card's `--orbit-angle` (set inline per card in the
          markup). --galaxy-dir mirrors the X axis so the inline-start
          arc stays visual-left in LTR and visual-right in RTL.
          Depth is angle-derived: cards on the upper arc of the orbit
          (sin < 0) read as nearer (larger, fully opaque); cards on the
          lower arc read as farther (smaller, dimmed). All cards are
          visible at once — no carousel, no queue. */
    .galaxy-card {
      position: absolute;
      flex: initial;
      max-width: none;
      /* 190px × 1.2 = 228px (Tomer asked for +20% on desktop). The orbit
         radii below were nudged proportionally so the larger cards don't
         crowd the orbit center or the rotate-controls. */
      width: 228px;
      cursor: pointer;
      top: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      /* Ellipse radii — clamped so the orbit shrinks gracefully on
         narrow desktop widths and grows on wide ones. Bumped to keep
         pace with the +20% card width. */
      --orbit-rx: clamp(310px, 34vw, 410px);
      --orbit-ry: clamp(160px, 22vh, 210px);
      /* Effective angle = base angle (set inline per card) + the
         stage-level rotation that the rotate-orbit controls drive.
         All trigonometry below reads from this so a single CSS-var
         change on the stage moves every card around the ellipse in
         lockstep, animated via the existing transform transition. */
      --orbit-active-angle: calc(var(--orbit-angle, 0deg) + var(--orbit-rotation, 0deg));
      /* Depth from angle: --orbit-depth ranges 0 (lower arc, farthest)
         to 1 (upper arc, nearest). sin(angle) is -1 at the top of the
         orbit and +1 at the bottom; `1 - sin` remaps so the UPPER arc
         reads as the near/front side and the lower arc recedes. */
      --orbit-depth: calc((1 - sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg))) / 2);
      /* Spatial depth ramp — front/near stations sit forward (scale
         1.0, full opacity, highest z-index), far/back stations recede
         (scale 0.68, 0.55 opacity, lowest z-index). Reads as a real
         perspective orbit, not a flat ring. Light mode lifts the
         opacity floor via the override block higher up. */
      --slot-scale: calc(0.68 + 0.32 * var(--orbit-depth));
      --slot-opacity: calc(0.55 + 0.45 * var(--orbit-depth));
      /* Subtle perpendicular tilt: cards on the inline-start arc
         (cos < 0 in default LTR, after dir flip) lean inward. */
      --tilt: calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * 4deg * var(--galaxy-dir, 1) * -1);
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(
          calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-rx) * var(--galaxy-dir, 1)),
          calc(sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-ry))
        )
        rotate(var(--tilt))
        scale(var(--slot-scale));
      opacity: var(--slot-opacity);
      transition:
        transform var(--orbit-motion-duration, 600ms)
                  var(--orbit-motion-ease, cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1)),
        opacity var(--orbit-motion-duration, 600ms)
                var(--orbit-motion-ease, cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1));
      /* Depth-sorted stacking: nearer cards layer above farther ones so
         overlaps read correctly. calc() resolves to a rounded integer,
         2 (back) .. 10 (front). Hover / linked-glow / focus sit above. */
      z-index: calc(2 + var(--orbit-depth) * 8);
      will-change: transform, opacity;
    }

    /* Type tint — books pick the gold accent rotation, lessons the
       cyan one, the course station the violet one. Keeps the groups
       visually distinct on the orbit without needing column-based
       layout. The course card picks up the purple accent already
       defined in the cosmic palette so it reads as part of the family
       without competing with the gold/cyan pairing of books and
       lessons. */
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="book"]   { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-gold); }
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="lesson"] { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-cyan); }
    .galaxy-card[data-kind="course"] { --card-accent-slot: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple); }

    /* Linked-glow halo ─────────────────────────────────────────────
       The artifact PNG (the visible book-card art) has transparent
       margins around the painted card pixels, so `box-shadow` on
       any container draws a rectangle far from the visible card
       edge. Solution: `filter: drop-shadow` on the artifact image
       itself — drop-shadow follows the alpha channel and lands on
       the actual painted silhouette of the card, regardless of the
       transparent padding around it.

       Three stacked drop-shadows per keyframe — a tight inner ring
       plus two soft outer blooms — produce a luminous halo that
       reads as a deliberate accent rather than a hard outline.
       Single-color turquoise pulse: the halo fades between a calm
       and an intensified state on a 1.5s loop, signalling the
       linked group without the multi-hue rotation. z-index on the
       wrapper rises during the pulse so highlighted cards float
       above neighbours.
       */
    .galaxy-card.is-linked-glow {
      /* Above every depth-sorted resting card (max z 10). */
      z-index: 11;
    }
    :global(.galaxy-card.is-linked-glow .lc-orbit-artifact-face-front) {
      animation: yuval-linked-glow 1.5s ease-in-out infinite;
    }
    @keyframes yuval-linked-glow {
      0%, 100% {
        filter:
          drop-shadow(0 0 2px  rgba(64, 224, 208, 1))
          drop-shadow(0 0 8px  rgba(64, 224, 208, 0.85))
          drop-shadow(0 0 18px rgba(64, 224, 208, 0.55));
      }
      50% {
        filter:
          drop-shadow(0 0 3px  rgba(64, 224, 208, 1))
          drop-shadow(0 0 12px rgba(64, 224, 208, 0.95))
          drop-shadow(0 0 26px rgba(64, 224, 208, 0.7));
      }
    }
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      :global(.galaxy-card.is-linked-glow .lc-orbit-artifact-face-front) {
        animation: none;
        filter:
          drop-shadow(0 0 2px  rgba(64, 224, 208, 1))
          drop-shadow(0 0 12px rgba(64, 224, 208, 0.55));
      }
    }

    /* Drag-to-rotate — while the user is actively dragging the orbit
       we drop the transform transition so the carousel tracks the
       cursor in real time (no easing lag). The transition is restored
       the moment the drag ends, which lets the snap-to-station read
       as a smooth animated move. The grabbing cursor + user-select
       reset prevent accidental text selection mid-drag. */
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-dragging],
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-dragging] .galaxy-card {
      cursor: grabbing;
      user-select: none;
      -webkit-user-select: none;
    }
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-dragging] .galaxy-card {
      transition: none;
    }
    /* Block the browser's native image/link drag on every card and on
       its descendant images. Without this, mousedown on the inner <a>
       starts a drag-and-drop "ghost" that prevents our pointermove
       handler from tracking the cursor. The pointerdown handler also
       calls preventDefault, but the CSS hint catches stragglers (e.g.
       SVG/IMG nodes that opt themselves into drag separately). */
    .galaxy-card,
    .galaxy-card *,
    .galaxy-card img,
    .galaxy-card svg {
      -webkit-user-drag: none;
    }

    /* ── Series capsule —
          Built client-side as a separate node when ≥2 visible items
          share a seriesName. The wrapper .galaxy-card carries the
          orbit positioning machinery so the capsule lives at a real
          station on the ellipse, exactly like a single-book card.
          Capsules are clickable: they enter series mode, expanding
          the series's books into a carousel and collapsing the rest
          of the universe into "Other Knowledge". */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"] {
      cursor: pointer;
      /* A capsule is wider than a regular book card on the orbit so the
         shape proportions alone signal "container, not item" — even
         before reading the badge or label. Scaled to keep the +10%
         ratio over the +20%-larger book card (228px → 252px). */
      width: 252px;
      /* Resolve series colour at the wrapper level so the deck pseudos
         (below) and the inner capsule both read the same value without
         each redefining it. */
      --series-color-resolved: var(--series-color, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-gold, #c9a96e));
    }
    /* Stacked deck — two ghost rectangles peeking out behind the capsule,
       narrower and offset downward so the capsule reads as a stack of
       grouped knowledge, not as a single tile. Pure decoration via
       wrapper pseudo-elements; muted/active state animations on the
       wrapper carry the deck along automatically. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]::before,
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]::after {
      content: "";
      position: absolute;
      pointer-events: none;
      border-radius: 18px;
      border-end-start-radius: 12px;
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 8%, var(--yuval-galaxy-card-surface, rgba(20, 22, 36, 0.78)));
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 22%, transparent);
      z-index: 0;
    }
    /* Middle layer — peeks 4 px below, narrower by 8 px each side. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]::after {
      inset-block-start: 4px;
      inset-block-end: -4px;
      inset-inline-start: 8px;
      inset-inline-end: 8px;
      opacity: 0.85;
    }
    /* Back layer — peeks 8 px below, narrower by 18 px each side. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]::before {
      inset-block-start: 7px;
      inset-block-end: -8px;
      inset-inline-start: 18px;
      inset-inline-end: 18px;
      opacity: 0.6;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]:focus-visible .galaxy-series-capsule {
      box-shadow:
        0 14px 38px -14px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 70%, transparent),
        0 0 0 2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 70%, transparent),
        inset 0 1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 22%, transparent);
    }

    /* ── Series members —
          Every individual book inside a multi-item series is kept in
          the DOM as an orbit card, but tagged with data-series-member
          so it stays hidden in universe mode. Series mode reveals the
          members of the active series via .is-active-series-member
          (added by the hydrator JS). */
    .galaxy-card[data-series-member] {
      display: none;
    }

    /* ── Series mode — stage-level state.
          Activated by clicking a SeriesCapsule. The hydrator sets
          data-stage-mode="series" + data-active-series="<name>" on
          the stage element, then class-tags individual cards. */

    /* Mute every station that isn't the active series's books or
       the synthesized Other Knowledge pill. Premium fade — opacity
       and scale only, no jarring movement. */
    [data-stage-mode="series"] .galaxy-card.is-muted {
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(
          calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-rx) * var(--galaxy-dir, 1) * 0.85),
          calc(sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-ry) * 0.85)
        )
        rotate(var(--tilt))
        scale(0.7);
    }

    /* The active series's own capsule is replaced by its books, so
       hide the capsule in series mode. */
    [data-stage-mode="series"] .galaxy-card.is-active-series-capsule {
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(
          calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-rx) * var(--galaxy-dir, 1)),
          calc(sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * var(--orbit-ry))
        )
        rotate(var(--tilt))
        scale(0.85);
    }

    /* Members of the active series — revealed and laid out in a
       horizontal carousel centered on the stage. The horizontal
       offset per card is computed from the index/total custom
       properties set by the hydrator. */
    [data-stage-mode="series"] .galaxy-card.is-active-series-member {
      display: block;
      --series-step: clamp(195px, 22vw, 230px);
      --series-row-x: calc(
        (var(--series-active-index, 0)
          - (var(--series-active-total, 1) - 1) / 2)
        * var(--series-step)
        * var(--galaxy-dir, 1)
      );
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(var(--series-row-x), 0)
        scale(1.12);
      opacity: 1;
      /* Series carousel members ride above the depth-sorted orbit
         (max z 10) so the collapsed "other knowledge" never overlaps. */
      z-index: 12;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

    /* Hover lift on a carousel book — gentle vertical bump only,
       overrides the default radial-bump hover so cards don't fly
       off the row. */
    [data-stage-mode="series"]
      .galaxy-card.is-active-series-member:hover:not([data-pos="center"]),
    [data-stage-mode="series"]
      .galaxy-card.is-active-series-member:focus-visible:not([data-pos="center"]) {
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(var(--series-row-x), -6px)
        scale(1.16);
      opacity: 1;
    }

    /* ── Other Knowledge capsule —
          Synthesized by JS on series-mode entry, removed on exit.
          Sits at the inline-end top of the stage as a compact pill
          summarising "everything else". Clicking it exits series
          mode and restores the universe. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="other-knowledge"] {
      /* Reset the orbit-card absolute geometry. */
      top: 0;
      left: auto;
      inset-block-start: 12px;
      inset-inline-end: 12px;
      width: auto;
      transform: none;
      opacity: 0;
      cursor: pointer;
      z-index: 6;
      transition:
        opacity 0.32s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        transform 0.32s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-role="other-knowledge"].is-visible {
      opacity: 1;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-role="other-knowledge"]:hover .galaxy-other-knowledge,
    .galaxy-card[data-role="other-knowledge"]:focus-visible .galaxy-other-knowledge {
      border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea) 30%, transparent);
      background: var(--yuval-galaxy-card-surface-hover, rgba(28, 30, 44, 0.82));
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-role="other-knowledge"]:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.6rem;
      padding: 0.55rem 0.85rem 0.55rem 0.65rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: var(--yuval-galaxy-card-surface, rgba(20, 22, 36, 0.78));
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted, #6e6e6c) 40%, transparent);
      backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      box-shadow: 0 8px 22px -10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
      transition: background 0.2s ease, border-color 0.2s ease;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge-icon {
      width: 26px;
      height: 26px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      display: grid;
      place-items: center;
      background: linear-gradient(
        180deg,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted, #6e6e6c) 20%, transparent),
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted, #6e6e6c) 8%, transparent)
      );
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      font-size: 1.15rem;
      line-height: 1;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      font-weight: 600;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge-text {
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 1px;
      line-height: 1.25;
      padding-inline-end: 0.15rem;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge-label {
      font-family: 'Spectral', 'Cardo', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      letter-spacing: 0.005em;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge-count {
      font-size: 0.66rem;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text-secondary, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted, #a8a8a4));
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    }

    .galaxy-other-knowledge-count strong {
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      font-weight: 600;
      margin-inline-end: 0.2rem;
    }

    .galaxy-series-capsule {
      position: relative;
      /* Stacked above the wrapper's deck pseudo-elements. */
      z-index: 1;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.45rem;
      padding: 1.05rem 1.1rem 0.85rem;
      padding-inline-start: 1.2rem;
      /* Restrained asymmetry — the inline-start/block-end corner is
         tighter so the capsule reads as a grounded container, not as
         a floating chip. Logical so RTL flips automatically. */
      border-radius: 22px;
      border-end-start-radius: 14px;
      background:
        /* Atmospheric inner glow from the top, painted with the series
           color. Lives in the background stack (not a pseudo-element)
           so children render above it without z-index gymnastics. */
        radial-gradient(
          ellipse 70% 55% at 50% 0%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 18%, transparent) 0%,
          transparent 65%
        ),
        linear-gradient(
          180deg,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 11%, transparent) 0%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 4%, transparent) 55%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 84%, transparent) 100%
        ),
        var(--yuval-galaxy-card-surface, rgba(20, 22, 36, 0.78));
      /* Two-layer luminous border — hairline outer ring + a slightly
         stronger inner edge — for a refined, lit-from-within feel. */
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 36%, transparent);
      box-shadow:
        0 10px 26px -16px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 38%, transparent),
        0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 14%, transparent),
        inset 0 1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 22%, transparent);
      backdrop-filter: blur(14px) saturate(125%);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(14px) saturate(125%);
      transition:
        border-color 240ms ease,
        box-shadow 240ms ease;
    }

    /* Capsule edge indicator — a thin luminous bar along the inline-start
       side, painted in the series color. Echoes the series swatch on
       /admin so the same color identifies the same series everywhere. */
    .galaxy-series-capsule::before {
      content: "";
      position: absolute;
      inset-block: 16px;
      inset-inline-start: 0;
      width: 2px;
      border-radius: 0 2px 2px 0;
      background: var(--series-color-resolved);
      opacity: 0.75;
      box-shadow: 0 0 8px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 60%, transparent);
    }
    [dir="rtl"] .galaxy-series-capsule::before {
      border-radius: 2px 0 0 2px;
    }

    /* Binder ridge — a hairline horizontal line tucked into the empty
       strip above the badge, like the metal clip at the top of a binder.
       Reads as "container surface" rather than "card top edge". */
    .galaxy-series-capsule::after {
      content: "";
      position: absolute;
      inset-block-start: 7px;
      inset-inline: 16px;
      height: 1px;
      pointer-events: none;
      background: linear-gradient(
        90deg,
        transparent 0%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 50%, transparent) 30%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 65%, transparent) 50%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 50%, transparent) 70%,
        transparent 100%
      );
      opacity: 0.55;
    }

    /* Restrained hover — slightly lift the border luminosity and the
       inner edge, no large bloom. The universe should feel calm. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"]:hover .galaxy-series-capsule {
      border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 52%, transparent);
      box-shadow:
        0 12px 30px -16px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 48%, transparent),
        0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 20%, transparent),
        inset 0 1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 28%, transparent);
    }

    .galaxy-series-badge {
      align-self: flex-start;
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      padding: 2px 10px 2px 8px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 18%, transparent);
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 55%, transparent);
      color: var(--series-color-resolved);
      font-family: 'Spectral', 'Cardo', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 0.66rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      letter-spacing: 0.14em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      line-height: 1.4;
    }
    /* Stacked-bars glyph rendered purely in CSS — three short horizontal
       lines tucked before the badge text. Reinforces the "stacked
       knowledge" semantic without adding markup. */
    .galaxy-series-badge::before {
      content: "";
      display: inline-block;
      width: 9px;
      height: 9px;
      margin-inline-end: 6px;
      background:
        linear-gradient(currentColor, currentColor) top center / 9px 1.4px no-repeat,
        linear-gradient(currentColor, currentColor) center      / 7px 1.4px no-repeat,
        linear-gradient(currentColor, currentColor) bottom center / 5px 1.4px no-repeat;
      vertical-align: -1px;
      opacity: 0.95;
    }

    .galaxy-series-name {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: 'Spectral', 'Cardo', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 1.12rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1.2;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
      /* Allow up to 2 lines — series names tend to be longer than book titles. */
      display: -webkit-box;
      -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
      line-clamp: 2;
      -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
      overflow: hidden;
    }

    .galaxy-series-counts {
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 1px;
      margin-top: 2px;
    }

    .galaxy-series-count-line {
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text-secondary, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted, #a8a8a4));
      line-height: 1.45;
      letter-spacing: 0.005em;
    }

    .galaxy-series-count-line strong {
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      font-family: 'Spectral', 'Cardo', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      font-feature-settings: 'tnum' 1, 'lnum' 1;
      margin-inline-end: 0.3rem;
    }

    .galaxy-series-count-available strong {
      color: var(--series-color-resolved);
    }

    /* Shelf — the spine row sits in a recessed compartment with a
       luminous bottom edge, so the spines read as "books on a shelf"
       rather than as a chart. Margin pulls the shelf to the inline
       edges of the capsule's inner padding so it spans the full width. */
    .galaxy-series-stack {
      position: relative;
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-end;
      gap: 3px;
      height: 18px;
      margin-block-start: 6px;
      margin-inline: -0.35rem;
      padding: 4px 0.5rem 5px;
      border-radius: 5px 5px 8px 8px;
      background:
        linear-gradient(
          180deg,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 22%, transparent) 0%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 42%, transparent) 100%
        );
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, #000 22%, transparent),
        inset 0 -1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 14%, transparent);
    }
    /* Luminous shelf line — the surface the books are resting on. */
    .galaxy-series-stack::after {
      content: "";
      position: absolute;
      inset-block-end: 1px;
      inset-inline: 8px;
      height: 1px;
      pointer-events: none;
      background: linear-gradient(
        90deg,
        transparent 0%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 60%, transparent) 50%,
        transparent 100%
      );
      opacity: 0.7;
    }
    /* Each spine = one book. Capped at 5 in the hydrator. Heights vary
       in a fixed, gentle rhythm — not random — so the row reads as
       "books on a shelf" without visual noise. */
    .galaxy-series-spine {
      display: block;
      width: 3px;
      border-radius: 1px 1px 0 0;
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 22%, transparent);
      height: 11px;
    }
    .galaxy-series-spine:nth-child(2) { height: 13px; }
    .galaxy-series-spine:nth-child(3) { height: 12px; }
    .galaxy-series-spine:nth-child(4) { height: 14px; }
    .galaxy-series-spine:nth-child(5) { height: 12px; }
    .galaxy-series-spine.is-filled {
      background: linear-gradient(
        180deg,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--series-color-resolved) 92%, white) 0%,
        var(--series-color-resolved) 100%
      );
      opacity: 0.85;
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 -1px 0 color-mix(in srgb, #000 25%, transparent);
    }

    /* Centered focus state — overrides the orbit transform so the card
       flies to the middle, scales up, drops its tilt. Sits above the
       backdrop and other cards.
       The extra `translateY(-90px)` after the scale anchors the focused
       card's TOP edge just below the hero subtitle so the reading
       "title → focused card" flow is continuous (Tomer asked for the
       centered card to start "right below the subtitle line", not
       mid-screen at the orbit center). Note: translateY appears AFTER
       scale(1.5) in the chain, but CSS applies transforms right-to-
       left, so the -90 px is multiplied through the 1.5× scale and
       reads as ~135 px visual upward shift. */
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] {
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%) scale(1.5) translateY(-90px);
      opacity: 1;
      z-index: 30;
      cursor: default;
    }

    /* Hover lift — small bump along the radial direction (cards move
       slightly further from center) plus a brightness/scale bump.
       Skipped when the card is focused to avoid double transforms. */
    .galaxy-card:hover:not([data-pos="center"]),
    .galaxy-card:focus-visible:not([data-pos="center"]) {
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -50%)
        translate(
          calc(cos(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * (var(--orbit-rx) + 8px) * var(--galaxy-dir, 1)),
          calc(sin(var(--orbit-active-angle, 0deg)) * (var(--orbit-ry) + 8px))
        )
        rotate(calc(var(--tilt) * 0.5))
        scale(calc(var(--slot-scale) * 1.04));
      opacity: 1;
      /* Lift above every depth-sorted resting card (max z 10) so a
         hovered card always comes forward, even from the back. */
      z-index: 11;
    }
    .galaxy-card:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
    }

    /* CTA overlay — hidden when card is in slot/queue; revealed only
       when data-pos="center". Children stop click propagation so the
       card-level handler never fires for Open/Close. */
    .galaxy-cta {
      position: absolute;
      /* Anchor inside the focused card at its visible bottom — the
         spot where the `.lc-orbit-author` byline used to sit before
         it was retired. Series action pills now read as part of the
         focused-card composition rather than as a side rail.
         Centering uses physical `left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%)`
         (not logical inset-inline-*) so it stays centered in both
         RTL Hebrew and LTR English without writing-direction quirks. */
      top: 66%;
      left: 50%;
      bottom: auto;
      right: auto;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      transition: opacity 0.25s ease 0.15s;
      /* Above the scaled-up artwork (`transform: scale(1.5)` visually
         bleeds past the card's flow box bottom by ~25%). */
      z-index: 2;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] .galaxy-cta {
      opacity: 1;
      pointer-events: auto;
    }
    /* ── Knowledge activation orb ─────────────────────────────────────
          Compact circular CTA that replaces the previous pill — feels
          native to the holographic knowledge-card universe rather than
          a generic web button. Layered structure:
            .galaxy-cta-open        — the orb body (translucent glass)
            .galaxy-cta-open-core   — inner radial light
            .galaxy-cta-open-ring   — outer dashed ring (rotates on hover)
            .galaxy-cta-open-icon   — the open/access glyph
            .galaxy-cta-open-label  — hover/focus tooltip
          Real <a> element with `aria-label`, so keyboard + screen-reader
          paths work exactly like the previous button (Enter/Space follow
          the link, focus-visible draws the same activated state). */
    .galaxy-cta-open {
      position: relative;
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      width: 64px;
      height: 64px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4);
      cursor: pointer;
      text-decoration: none;
      /* Translucent glass body — inner glow rooted on the accent,
         fading into the page background colour at the edges. The
         core layer (::core span below) handles the brighter centre. */
      background:
        radial-gradient(
          circle at 50% 38%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 24%, transparent) 0%,
          color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 8%, transparent) 55%,
          transparent 100%
        ),
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 55%, transparent);
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 60%, transparent);
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 18%, transparent) inset,
        0 0 6px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 50%, transparent) inset,
        0 0 18px -2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 35%, transparent);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      transition:
        transform 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        box-shadow 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        border-color 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
      /* Subtle continuous breathing — the orb feels alive even at rest. */
      animation: galaxy-cta-open-pulse 3.6s ease-in-out infinite;
    }
    @keyframes galaxy-cta-open-pulse {
      0%, 100% {
        box-shadow:
          0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 18%, transparent) inset,
          0 0 6px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 50%, transparent) inset,
          0 0 18px -2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 35%, transparent);
      }
      50% {
        box-shadow:
          0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 26%, transparent) inset,
          0 0 8px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 60%, transparent) inset,
          0 0 24px -2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 45%, transparent);
      }
    }
    /* Inner core highlight — small luminous spot toward the upper-left
       of the orb, like a glass marble's reflected light source. */
    .galaxy-cta-open-core {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 18%;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background: radial-gradient(
        circle at 38% 30%,
        color-mix(in srgb, white 35%, transparent) 0%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 22%, transparent) 28%,
        transparent 70%
      );
      pointer-events: none;
    }
    /* Outer dashed ring — sits just outside the orb. Rotates slowly
       on hover/focus; static + slightly dimmer at rest. */
    .galaxy-cta-open-ring {
      position: absolute;
      inset: -5px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      border: 1px dashed
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 45%, transparent);
      opacity: 0.7;
      pointer-events: none;
      transition: opacity 220ms ease;
    }
    @keyframes galaxy-cta-open-ring-rotate {
      from { transform: rotate(0deg); }
      to   { transform: rotate(360deg); }
    }
    /* Open/access glyph — chevron into the inline-end direction. RTL
       mirroring is handled below so "→" stays reading-flow forward. */
    .galaxy-cta-open-icon {
      position: relative;
      width: 22px;
      height: 22px;
      z-index: 1;
      filter: drop-shadow(
        0 0 6px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 65%, transparent));
      transition: opacity 180ms ease;
    }
    [dir="rtl"] .galaxy-cta-open-icon { transform: scaleX(-1); }

    /* Hover label — floats to the PHYSICAL RIGHT of the orb,
       vertically centered on the orb. Physical `left` + `top` (not
       `inset-inline-*`) so the side stays the same in both RTL and
       LTR — the user explicitly asked for visual-right. The 4px
       inward initial translation gives a small slide-in entry. */
    .galaxy-cta-open-label {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%;
      left: calc(100% + 0.5rem);
      bottom: auto;
      right: auto;
      inset-block-start: auto;
      inset-block-end: auto;
      inset-inline-start: auto;
      inset-inline-end: auto;
      transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(-4px);
      padding: 0.25rem 0.625rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      font-family: 'Assistant', system-ui, sans-serif;
      font-size: 0.78125rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      letter-spacing: 0.01em;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 82%, transparent);
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 28%, transparent);
      backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
      white-space: nowrap;
      pointer-events: none;
      opacity: 0;
      transition:
        opacity 180ms ease,
        transform 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
    }

    .galaxy-cta-open:hover,
    .galaxy-cta-open:focus-visible {
      transform: translateY(-2px);
      border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 80%, transparent);
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 30%, transparent) inset,
        0 0 8px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 70%, transparent) inset,
        0 0 28px -2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 55%, transparent),
        0 0 14px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent, #5eead4) 35%, transparent);
      outline: none;
      /* Pause the rest pulse — hover/focus drives its own glow now. */
      animation-play-state: paused;
    }
    .galaxy-cta-open:hover .galaxy-cta-open-ring,
    .galaxy-cta-open:focus-visible .galaxy-cta-open-ring {
      opacity: 1;
      animation: galaxy-cta-open-ring-rotate 12s linear infinite;
    }
    /* Icon stays visible on hover — the label is its own bubble
       above the orb now, no swap needed. */
    .galaxy-cta-open:hover .galaxy-cta-open-label,
    .galaxy-cta-open:focus-visible .galaxy-cta-open-label {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(0);
    }
    .galaxy-cta-open:active {
      transform: translateY(0);
      transition-duration: 80ms;
    }

    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .galaxy-cta-open,
      .galaxy-cta-open-icon,
      .galaxy-cta-open-label,
      .galaxy-cta-open-ring { transition: none; animation: none; }
      .galaxy-cta-open:hover .galaxy-cta-open-ring,
      .galaxy-cta-open:focus-visible .galaxy-cta-open-ring { animation: none; }
    }
    .galaxy-cta-close {
      width: 28px;
      height: 28px;
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      border-radius: 50%;
      font-size: 1.125rem;
      line-height: 1;
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text-muted);
      background: var(--yuval-galaxy-surface-muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--yuval-galaxy-border);
      cursor: pointer;
      padding: 0;
      transition: color 0.15s ease, background-color 0.15s ease, border-color 0.15s ease;
    }
    .galaxy-cta-close:hover,
    .galaxy-cta-close:focus-visible {
      color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text);
      background: var(--yuval-galaxy-card-surface-hover);
      border-color: var(--yuval-galaxy-border-strong);
      outline: none;
    }

    /* ── Reading-entry overlay (phase 1) ─────────────────────────────
       Internal premium panel that appears ONLY when the card is
       centered (`[data-pos="center"]`). Sits absolutely over the card
       surface, between the LibraryCard art and the close button.
       Routing is not wired yet — the click handler in
       `initReadingEntry()` (see the page script block) logs slug + href.

       The original side open orb (`.galaxy-cta-open`) is hidden via
       the `display: none` rule below; the underlying <a href> is left
       in the DOM so we keep the link target for future use. */
    .galaxy-cta-open {
      display: none !important;
    }

    /* ── Reading-entry overlay: in-card image-based premium panel ──────
       The entry control sits INSIDE the centered book card (not below
       it). The visual is a textless PNG asset; all visible text is
       live, localized HTML rendered on top — the image never carries
       baked text.

       Stacking inside the overlay <a>:
         .reading-entry-asset  — background-image PNG (decorative)
         .reading-entry-text   — title + subtitle, live i18n

       The <a> itself is the hit area and preserves native link
       behavior (Ctrl/Cmd-click → new tab, middle-click → new tab,
       right-click → context menu). Plain left-click and Enter are
       intercepted by the launch handler in `universe-layout.ts` via
       the `data-reading-entry` attribute.

       Phase-3 launch animation: the overlay's two child layers
       (.reading-entry-asset + .reading-entry-text) fade out cleanly
       when `data-reading-entry-state="opening"` is set on the stage.
       Opacity-only fade keeps the link in the accessibility tree
       until the launch is committed. */
    /* Image-based reading-entry panel. The visual base IS the
       `reading-entry-card1.png` asset — it carries the icon (top
       center), the glass background, the border and the glow.
       Title, subtitle AND the lesson meta row all live INSIDE this
       single panel (not in a separate section below) so the CTA and
       its facts read as one premium glass surface.

       Width math: `calc(85% * 1.5)` resolves to 127.5% of the parent
       box. Combined with the parent's 1.5× scale and this element's
       1/1.5 counter-scale, the visible CTA renders at exactly 85% of
       the visible card width. */
    .reading-entry-overlay {
      position: absolute;
      left: 50%;
      /* 18px visible gap below the cover's visible bottom. Cover
         visible bottom sits ~42px above the card's flow-box bottom
         (lc-orbit ~28px padding × 1.5 parent scale). For an 18px
         visible gap, the CTA's visible top should land 24px below
         the flow-box bottom; in box space that's 24/1.5 = 16px. */
      top: calc(100% - 16px);
      width: calc(85% * 1.5);
      max-width: 620px;
      min-width: 420px;
      /* Height bumped from 220 → 240 to give the new summary pill +
         meta row clear vertical room without clipping. */
      height: 240px;
      border-radius: 28px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      transform: translate(-50%, 0) scale(calc(1 / 1.5));
      transform-origin: top center;
      display: block;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      border: 0;
      background: transparent;
      color: inherit;
      -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
      opacity: 0;
      visibility: hidden;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 30;
      transition:
        transform 180ms ease,
        filter 180ms ease,
        opacity 240ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        visibility 0s linear 240ms;
    }
    .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] .reading-entry-overlay {
      opacity: 1;
      visibility: visible;
      pointer-events: auto;
      transition:
        transform 180ms ease,
        filter 180ms ease,
        opacity 240ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        visibility 0s linear 0s;
    }
    /* Main click target — transparent <a> stretched over the panel
       so any click that isn't on the summary pill continues reading.
       Sits BELOW the asset visually (z-index handled by stacking
       order; `.reading-entry-asset` paints on top with pointer-
       events:none, so the link still receives clicks underneath). */
    .reading-entry-main {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      display: block;
      border-radius: 28px;
      background: transparent;
      color: inherit;
      text-decoration: none;
      cursor: pointer;
      z-index: 1;
      -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
    }
    .reading-entry-main:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
    }
    .reading-entry-main:focus-visible ~ .reading-entry-asset {
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(150, 200, 255, 0.45),
        0 0 22px rgba(112, 87, 255, 0.45);
    }

    /* The PNG IS the panel — painted edge-to-edge over the main link.
       `pointer-events: none` so the transparent `.reading-entry-main`
       below it still receives every click that isn't on the pill. */
    .reading-entry-asset {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      border-radius: 28px;
      background-image: url('/assets/ui/reading-entry/reading-entry-card1.png');
      background-size: 100% 100%;
      background-repeat: no-repeat;
      background-position: center;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 2;
      transition:
        transform 220ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        box-shadow 220ms ease,
        filter 220ms ease;
    }

    /* Live i18n stack — title, subtitle, summary pill, then the meta
       row. Positioned ABSOLUTELY over the lower portion of the asset
       so the icon baked into the PNG stays clear at the top center.
       Container itself is `pointer-events: none` so empty space and
       text below pass clicks through to `.reading-entry-main`; the
       pill re-opts in to pointer events below. */
    .reading-entry-text {
      position: absolute;
      left: 50%;
      top: 58%;
      width: 92%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: 8px;
      text-align: center;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 3;
      font-family:
        'Heebo', 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system,
        'Segoe UI', 'Noto Sans Hebrew', sans-serif;
    }
    .reading-entry-title {
      font-size: 32px;
      font-weight: 700;
      line-height: 1.05;
      letter-spacing: 0;
      white-space: nowrap;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.96);
      text-shadow:
        0 0 12px rgba(120, 180, 255, 0.30),
        0 2px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      margin: 0;
    }
    .reading-entry-subtitle {
      font-size: 18px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1.2;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72);
      white-space: nowrap;
      text-shadow: 0 1px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.45);
      margin: 0;
    }

    /* Secondary "Book summary" pill — visually quieter than the title
       and the meta chips so it reads as an alternate action, never as
       a competing CTA. Subtle glass: dark translucent fill, thin blue
       border, white text. `pointer-events: auto` re-opts this single
       node back into hit-testing, so empty-space clicks still fall
       through to `.reading-entry-main`. */
    .reading-entry-summary-pill {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      height: 26px;
      padding: 0 14px;
      margin: 2px 0 0;
      border-radius: 999px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      font-size: 12px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1;
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
      color: rgba(245, 250, 255, 0.92);
      background: rgba(8, 18, 40, 0.55);
      border: 1px solid rgba(120, 175, 235, 0.42);
      text-decoration: none;
      text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      pointer-events: auto;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition:
        background 160ms ease,
        border-color 160ms ease,
        color 160ms ease,
        transform 160ms ease;
    }
    .reading-entry-summary-pill:hover {
      background: rgba(18, 32, 60, 0.7);
      border-color: rgba(150, 200, 245, 0.6);
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 1);
    }
    .reading-entry-summary-pill:active {
      transform: scale(0.97);
    }
    .reading-entry-summary-pill:focus-visible {
      outline: none;
      box-shadow:
        0 0 0 2px rgba(150, 200, 255, 0.45),
        0 0 14px rgba(112, 87, 255, 0.35);
    }

    /* Hover / active — translate + brightness lift on the asset and a
       tiny press-in scale. Targets the main link so hovering the
       summary pill (a sibling, not an ancestor) does NOT also trigger
       the main-CTA lift — that's what keeps the two actions visually
       distinct. The translate is added to the overlay's existing
       counter-scale matrix on the parent. */
    .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:hover) {
      transform:
        translate(-50%, -2px)
        scale(calc(1 / 1.5));
      filter: brightness(1.08);
    }
    .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:hover) .reading-entry-asset {
      filter: brightness(1.04) saturate(1.05);
    }
    .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:active) {
      transform:
        translate(-50%, 0)
        scale(calc((1 / 1.5) * 0.985));
      filter: none;
    }
    .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:active) .reading-entry-asset {
      filter: none;
    }

    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .reading-entry-overlay,
      .reading-entry-asset,
      .reading-entry-summary-pill {
        transition: none;
      }
      .reading-entry-overlay:has(.reading-entry-main:hover) {
        transform: translate(-50%, 0) scale(calc(1 / 1.5));
        filter: none;
      }
    }

    /* The standalone `.center-card-extras` wrapper was retired — the
       meta row now lives INSIDE the reading-entry panel itself. The
       wrapper, secondary link and section label are still defined in
       the DOM/CSS only as dead cohabitants of the panel block; both
       are pinned to display:none below so they never paint. */
    .center-card-extras,
    .cc-secondary-link,
    .cc-meta-label {
      display: none;
    }

    /* In-panel lesson meta row — sits as the bottom child of
       `.reading-entry-text`, so it inherits the panel's centered axis
       and the same counter-scale (no extra positioning needed). Chips
       stay lightweight so they read as scannable facts under the CTA
       headline, not as competing controls. */
    .cc-meta {
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: row;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 8px;
      font-family:
        'Heebo', 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system,
        'Segoe UI', 'Noto Sans Hebrew', sans-serif;
    }
    .cc-meta-item {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      height: 30px;
      padding: 0 12px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      box-sizing: border-box;
      font-size: 13px;
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1;
      color: rgba(235, 242, 255, 0.92);
      white-space: nowrap;
      background: rgba(8, 18, 40, 0.55);
      border: 1px solid rgba(130, 180, 240, 0.28);
      text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
    }
    /* The legacy middot separator is incompatible with the chip layout. */
    .cc-meta-item + .cc-meta-item::before {
      content: none;
    }

    /* Match the pill's launch fade — when the user activates the
       primary action and the stage flips into the opening state,
       quietly fade the extras out too so they don't linger after
       the pill is gone. Opacity-only keeps the secondary link in
       the a11y tree until navigation fires. */
    .library-galaxy[data-reading-entry-state="opening"]
      .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"]
      .center-card-extras {
      opacity: 0;
      transition: opacity 100ms ease-out;
    }

    /* ── Reading-entry confirmation ─────────────────────────────────
       Minimal confirmation transition for the reading-button click.
       The earlier cinematic portal (seam + aura + scan + neural nodes
       + scene/hero dim + camera push) was retired — Tomer asked for a
       mature, professional, fast handoff. What survives:
         1. The reading-entry pill fades out quickly (~100ms).
         2. The selected card gets a very subtle cyan halo + brightness
            lift (~200ms).
         3. JS navigates to the same href after ~200ms.

       Carousel focus (recede on non-centred cards, scale on centred)
       lives in its own block below and is independent — it runs on
       every card-centring event, not just on launch.

       Tunables on `:root` so JS and CSS share one source of truth.
       JS reads `--reading-entry-total` via getComputedStyle and uses
       it as the setTimeout delay before navigation. */
    :root {
      --reading-entry-total: 200ms;
      --reading-entry-ease: cubic-bezier(0.22, 0.61, 0.36, 1);
      --reading-entry-halo-color: rgba(120, 210, 255, 0.45);
    }

    /* Pill fade — the user just activated it, so its job is done.
       Opacity-only so the link itself stays in the accessibility tree
       until the navigation timer fires. */
    .library-galaxy[data-reading-entry-state="opening"]
      .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"]
      .reading-entry-asset,
    .library-galaxy[data-reading-entry-state="opening"]
      .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"]
      .reading-entry-text {
      opacity: 0;
      transition: opacity 100ms ease-out;
    }

    /* Subtle confirmation on the selected card — a small brightness
       lift plus a single cyan halo that traces the artifact's alpha
       silhouette via drop-shadow. Calibrated to read as "the AI heard
       you" within 200ms, without theatrics. */
    .library-galaxy[data-reading-entry-state="opening"]
      .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] :global(.lc-orbit-artifact-face-front) {
      filter:
        brightness(1.05)
        drop-shadow(0 0 8px var(--reading-entry-halo-color));
      transition: filter var(--reading-entry-total) var(--reading-entry-ease);
    }

    /* ── Carousel focus: non-centred cards recede ─────────────────────
       Trigger is `data-galaxy-focused` on the stage (set by
       universe-layout.ts whenever a card is centred), NOT the launch-
       state attribute. The recede is a NORMAL carousel-focus behaviour:
       pick any card via orbit navigation and the rest of the field
       recedes immediately — no reading-button click required.

       `scale` is the individual CSS property (not `transform: scale`)
       so it composes after the orbit's cos/sin transform without us
       having to recompute coordinates here. Transition runs at 0.4s
       to match the orbit's snappy focus pace. */
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused]
      .galaxy-card:not([data-pos="center"]) {
      filter: blur(3px) saturate(0.78);
      opacity: 0.28;
      scale: 0.86;
      transition:
        filter 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        opacity 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
        scale 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
    }

    /* Reduced motion: skip both the confirmation halo and the focus
       recede. JS short-circuits with location.assign before any state
       flip too, so these rules are belt-and-braces for any code path
       that sets the state without the JS guard. */
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .library-galaxy[data-reading-entry-state="opening"]
        .galaxy-card[data-pos="center"] :global(.lc-orbit-artifact-face-front) {
        filter: none;
        transition: none;
      }
      .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused]
        .galaxy-card:not([data-pos="center"]) {
        transition: none;
        scale: 1;
        filter: none;
        opacity: 1;
      }
    }

    /* Click-catcher only — covers the stage when a card is focused so
       a click anywhere outside the centered card closes the focus
       state. No visible fill / no blur layer: the focused card is its
       own focal point now (1.5× scale, larger artifact, layered text),
       and the wide blur was reading as a heavy panel behind the
       artifact rather than helping the focal lift. */
    .galaxy-backdrop {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      background: transparent;
      backdrop-filter: none;
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: none;
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 15;
    }
    .library-galaxy[data-galaxy-focused] .galaxy-backdrop {
      /* Stays invisible — only its hitbox matters. opacity:1 just lets
         pointer-events register; it has nothing to render. */
      opacity: 1;
      pointer-events: auto;
    }
    /* Focus state used to dim the centered PNG so the focused card
       read as the new focal point. With the galaxy now rendered as
       a full-viewport scene background, the `.galaxy-backdrop` blur+
       darken layer above the orbit already provides that focal lift,
       so no extra dimming is wired here. */

    /* Orbit rotation controls — chevron pair pinned to the bottom of
       the viewport (not the stage), so they sit clear of the orbit
       cards at every breakpoint and remain a large, easy click target.
       Each click bumps --orbit-rotation on the stage by ±360°/N, and
       CSS interpolates the resulting transform on every card
       simultaneously. The wrapper is a flex pill so the two buttons
       read as one control. */
    .galaxy-orbit-controls {
      /* Always pinned to the very bottom of the viewport on desktop
         too. Only the safe-area-inset-bottom is honored on top —
         same hard-edge anchoring as the mobile rule above. */
      position: fixed !important;
      inset-block-end: auto;
      bottom: env(safe-area-inset-bottom, 0px) !important;
      left: 0;
      right: 0;
      margin-inline: auto;
      display: flex;
      width: max-content;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.3125rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12);
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.18),
        0 6px 18px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.30);
      backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
      z-index: 40;
      direction: ltr;
    }
    .galaxy-orbit-btn {
      /* Compact rotate control — small pearl glass circle. Slightly
         brighter than the previous muted-surface version so the icons
         read clearly without competing with the book cards. */
      width: 30px;
      height: 30px;
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      border-radius: 50%;
      color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.10);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.22);
      box-shadow:
        inset 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.28),
        0 2px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.24);
      cursor: pointer;
      padding: 0;
      transition: color 0.15s ease, background-color 0.15s ease, border-color 0.15s ease, transform 0.15s ease;
    }
    .galaxy-orbit-btn:hover,
    .galaxy-orbit-btn:focus-visible {
      color: #ffffff;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.18);
      border-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.36);
      transform: translateY(-1px);
      outline: none;
    }
    /* Mirror chevrons on RTL pages so "next" still points toward the
       direction reading flows. The stage itself is direction:ltr;
       only the icons need the manual flip. */
    [dir="rtl"] .galaxy-orbit-btn svg { transform: scaleX(-1); }

  }

  /* ── Wide desktop (≥1280px): wider orbit cards + larger orbit. ─── */
  @media (min-width: 1280px) {
    /* Larger orbit scene gets a deeper vertical offset so rotating
       cards along the wider ellipse still clear the page title.
       Wide desktop carries a slightly bigger orbit-ry (up to 250px
       vs the 1024-1279px tier's 230px), so the offset adds another
       +20px on top of the base desktop's new 90px to preserve the
       minimum ~20px top-card clearance Tomer requested.
       Reduced from 110→70 (paired with --orbit-ry shrinking by the
       same ~40px) so the orbit becomes shorter on wide desktops too
       while the TOP of the carousel stays at the same Y as before. */
    .library-galaxy {
      --orbit-vertical-offset: 70px;
    }
    .galaxy-card {
      /* 210px × 1.2 = 252px (Tomer's +20% bump). Orbit radii grown
         proportionally so the wider cards still distribute cleanly. */
      width: 252px;
      --orbit-rx: clamp(350px, 33vw, 480px);
      --orbit-ry: clamp(180px, 22vh, 235px);
    }
    /* Capsule stays one notch wider than a book card so the proportion
       contrast holds across breakpoints. 232 × 1.2 = 278px. */
    .galaxy-card[data-role="series"] {
      width: 278px;
    }
  }

  /* ── Series action panel — shown next to a focused series capsule ──
        Two pill buttons that ride along inside the existing
        `.galaxy-cta` slot. The slot's fade-in / pointer-events rule
        already gates visibility on `[data-pos="center"]`, so these
        buttons inherit the same focus-only reveal as the close button
        without any extra logic.
        Only the course card (`data-kind="course"`) ever renders the
        wrapper, so other cards remain unchanged. */
  .galaxy-cta-series-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    align-items: stretch;
    margin-block-start: 0.25rem;
  }
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 0.4375rem 0.75rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    font-family: 'Spectral', 'Cardo', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 0.78125rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 78%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 38%, transparent);
    cursor: pointer;
    backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
    transition:
      background-color 180ms ease,
      border-color 180ms ease,
      transform 180ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
      box-shadow 180ms ease;
    text-align: start;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn:hover,
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn:focus-visible {
    outline: none;
    transform: translateY(-1px);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 60%, transparent);
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 70%, transparent);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 22%, transparent) inset,
      0 0 14px -2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 45%, transparent);
  }
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn[aria-pressed="true"] {
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 16%, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d));
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 70%, transparent);
  }
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn-icon {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 18px;
    height: 18px;
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa);
    flex: 0 0 auto;
  }
  .galaxy-cta-series-btn-label {
    line-height: 1.1;
  }

  /* ── Local children fan — opens around the focused series capsule ──
        The fan is a horizontal row of small child cards positioned
        under the focused capsule. It lives inside the orbit stage as
        a positioned overlay so it never permanently mixes into the
        main universe. Hidden until the controller populates it; the
        controller also clears its contents on close so leftover state
        never lingers. */
  .series-children-fan[hidden] { display: none; }
  .series-children-fan {
    position: absolute;
    inset-inline: 0;
    inset-block-end: 1.25rem;
    z-index: 25; /* above orbit cards (3), below focused card (30) */
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    pointer-events: none;
    padding-inline: 1rem;
  }
  .series-children-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0.625rem 0.875rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.625rem;
    pointer-events: auto;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 75%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 28%, transparent);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 1px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 12%, transparent) inset,
      0 18px 40px -16px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 40%, transparent);
    max-width: min(640px, 92%);
    animation: series-children-fade-in 240ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
  }
  @keyframes series-children-fade-in {
    from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(8px); }
    to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
  }
  .series-children-empty {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0.875rem 1.125rem;
    pointer-events: auto;
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text-soft);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 75%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 28%, transparent);
    border-radius: 999px;
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    text-align: center;
  }
  .series-child-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: stretch;
    width: 96px;
    padding: 0.4375rem;
    border-radius: 0.625rem;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 65%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-border, rgba(120, 130, 165, 0.22)) 70%, transparent);
    transition: border-color 160ms ease, transform 160ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
  }
  .series-child-card:hover {
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 55%, transparent);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }
  .series-child-visual {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    overflow: hidden;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    background:
      radial-gradient(
        circle at 50% 35%,
        color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 18%, transparent) 0%,
        transparent 70%
      ),
      var(--yuval-galaxy-surface-muted, #161a2c);
  }
  .series-child-visual img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: contain;
    display: block;
    user-select: none;
    -webkit-user-drag: none;
  }
  .series-child-visual-placeholder {
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.25rem;
    color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 75%, var(--yuval-galaxy-text-soft, #c8c8c4));
  }
  .series-child-placeholder-glyph {
    display: inline-flex;
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 6px color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa) 50%, transparent));
  }
  .series-child-placeholder-type {
    font-size: 0.625rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text-soft, #c8c8c4);
    opacity: 0.85;
  }
  .series-child-title {
    margin: 0.4375rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    color: var(--yuval-galaxy-text, #ececea);
    text-align: center;
    display: -webkit-box;
    -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
    line-clamp: 2;
    -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  /* ── Series details drawer — same-page modal ───────────────────────
        Right-anchored (logical inline-end) sliding drawer that opens
        when the user clicks "Series details" on a focused capsule.
        Uses a real <aside role="dialog" aria-modal="true"> so screen
        readers and keyboard users get a proper modal surface. The
        overlay is a sibling click-catcher; it does not blur to keep
        the cosmic backdrop visible. */
  .series-details-overlay[hidden],
  .series-details-drawer[hidden] { display: none !important; }
  .series-details-overlay {
    position: fixed;
    inset: 0;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 70%, transparent);
    backdrop-filter: blur(4px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(4px);
    z-index: 90;
    animation: series-details-overlay-in 220ms ease-out;
  }
  @keyframes series-details-overlay-in {
    from { opacity: 0; }
    to   { opacity: 1; }
  }
  .series-details-drawer {
    position: fixed;
    inset-block: 0;
    inset-inline-end: 0;
    inset-inline-start: auto;
    width: min(420px, 100vw);
    max-width: 100vw;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--yuval-galaxy-bg, #00010d) 92%, var(--yuval-galaxy-accent-purple, #a78bfa));
